deck_excerpt: Offer a silent prayer (and steal stuff) with Kashtira Voiceless Voice!
deck_description:
Voiceless Voice is a very potent deck in the specific space of Master Duel's format. It plays well into Maxx 'C', liberal space for non-engine to pack outs to problem board states, enough power and resillience to deal with opponents' attempts to kill you, and has ways around most common handtraps (except Gamma, but that bozo's functionally leaving the format in a week so even that won't be a problem). While Yubel and Tenpai are presently superior decks, Voiceless Voice stands as one of their unsung rivals.

The only question was how you wanted to build the deck. Branded and Dogmatika were common choices in the TCG, but Branded's limits in MD make that a non-starter IMO and Dogmatika just doesn't have the punch I'm looking for. Pure VV was, of course, an option (and how I played it in the past, I have a deck profile for pure from a few months ago).

Then I encountered the concept of Kashtira Voiceless Voice. I forget what gave me this idea, whether it was running into it in Ranked or seeing a decklist on YGOPRO or even just thinking about Kashtira Snake-Eyes (for those who remember that innovation from the MD playerbase), but here it is. I won't go into the card-by-card, but here's some reasoning on why I've built it this way:

  • Kashtira is an engine that can be played before starting your main VV line without any issue. Drawing Unicorn or Wraitsoth is full Kash combo, and both baits out handtraps and disincentivizes your opponent from handtrapping the VV line by way of Unicorn's presence. It can also be performed without running into Nibiru by pausing your Kashtira combo after Unicorn's search, running through the VV line from there, then continuing after Skull Guardian's negate is online. It also means you're less likely to brick on non-engine, since three Kashtira cards are straight one-card combos and there's some two card combos that can all result in Shangri+Ariseheart on field even if you don't draw a VV card.
  • In a similar vein, the Kashtiras are also a good source of tribute fodder for the VV Rituals. They're all level 7 (except Riseheart, but he can even make himself a 7 if you're truly desperate), meaning you can use them as the whole material when summoning with Saffira's GY effect. Note that not being LIGHT means they cannot be used for a Ritual Summon with Prayers, however.
  • Kashtira also functions as a strong extra end-board set-up. Ariseheart is a walking Macros Cosmos with a huge attack stat and removal (and under Barrier, cannot be targeted for attack while Lo+Skull Guardian are present), which means he can often shut down turns on his own.
  • On the other end, Voiceless Voice is able to tolerate Ariseheart's presence as an end-board piece as long as you're not an idiot. Blessing lets you recur banished cards, and as long as you don't tribute Lo while Ariseheart's on the field you can generally get away with having him there.
  • Tenpai also has a decent amount of difficulty playing through Voiceless Voice if you can get Sauravis, Ancient and Ascended onto the field. While they theoretically have ways around it, a lot of Tenpai players will run straight into Sauravis by summoning Bident (at which point you can just use Sauravis to banish it before it even technically hits the field, removing it from being a problem at all). Prayers also lets us swiftly recover from most of Tenpai's destruction-based board-breakers, summoning Skull Guardian then reviving Lo to turn the negate back online.
  • We also main-deck 2x Evenly Matched as our primary board-breaker. It's half-economic purposes (Evenly is the best SR rarity board-breaker), but also that I find it preferable in most match-ups over other options. It's especially strong into Yubel, who is probably the best going-first deck in the format right now.
  • Imperm is probably the hand-trap I fear most right now, on grounds that it dodges Triple Tactics Talent and Called By (two of the anti-handtrap tools we run), meaning we need to hard-open Sauravis to fully be safe on protecting our activations.
  • Extra Deck is definitely very flexible. I rarely ever actually use any of these cards outside of the Kashtira line, so feel free to experiment.
  • Droll & Lock Bird is very bad if it is activated on our turn, but it also is not especially common in this format right now. We can manage if we hard-open Lo+Skull Guardian, but otherwise you will have to figure out a line on your own based on your hand. There's not a lot of good options, sadly.

Somehow this deck works pretty good. I never saw anyone using Hero Kid as an extender for Live Twin + Spright. You can also use Senri and Saambel to special summon it from hand or graveyard. You can send one Blue Spright to the graveyard using Sprind and pickup the card with Herald, special summoning it to the field.
Simple Witchcrafter Deck for someone wanting to learn the deck and try out Yugioh for the fist time
Love this deck, some of the best deck around.

deck_name: 40 card all bricks vol. 2 if i had infinite money
Locals: Tistina FIRST PLACE UNDEFEATED out of 14 players [ROTA Celebration Event] [30.11.2024]
deck_excerpt: Locals: Tistina FIRST PLACE UNDEFEATED out of 14 players [ROTA Celebration Event] [30.11.2024]
deck_description:
Round 1 vs Sharks ( 2 - 1 )

Round 2 vs Fiendsmith Azamina Snake-Eyes ( 2 - 1 )

Round 3 vs Runick Branded Bystial Synchro ( 2 - 0 )

Round 4 vs Bystial Centurion ( 2 - 1 )

 

Engine is pretty much set in stone for me. Terrortop is crazy because he sets up more combos using Levirtue Dragon and helps playing through handtraps using Totembird or Gossip Shadow. I dont main Virtue Stream though because you mostly just make Levirtue Dragon when you draw terrortop while Silhouhatte Rabbit can always be made and works under droll, playing both is too many bricks.

Non-engine was nice, would probably run more handtraps instead of Fenrir though. Daruma Cannon was busted again, even going second it just forces a grindgame which this deck mostly wins.

played 42 because I felt like with 40 you draw too many duplicates. With my next lists I will stay at 42 - 44.

Nothing too special in the extra deck. 2 Varudras is mandatory, I play 3 just in case. Lyna sadly didnt come up, but dont know if I would swap her for Knightmare Phoenix again. Lyna is nice if you want to make S:P and can search Demigod if you crash with her.

In the side deck, im honestly just trying out some things. I always play Ultimate Slayer + Targets, Thrust, Talents, Duster and now Dbarrier too. I also side Virtue Stream for going first.

I sided Phantazmay but never found him, same with Cosmic Cyclone. They could theoretically have been pretty good still so I dont know if I will keep them in the side deck or not.

 

Overall Im extremely happy with that list. The only things you could maybe improve is playing a small fiendsmith engine, but I havent tried that yet and it might not even be the right decision because of how many extra deck slots it requires.

deck_excerpt: Infinitrack aiming to Special Summon Arise-Heart.
deck_description:
The main goal of the deck is to SS Arise-Heart through Outrigger Extension. There is several road to do that. The only one card access to Arise-Heart is using the SHS engine but it can do so much better things in this deck. I give after this some combo lines often used. The end board is usually composed of an Arise-Heart supported by Outrigger Extension and Infinitrack Road Roller , a Cyber Dragon Infinity and either a S:P Little Knight or a Karakuri Super Shogun mdl 00N "Bureibu" .

 

Infinitrack Combo : The main downside of the Infinitrack line is that it is not a one card combo. To perform the combo you need to have Infinitrack Harvester or Heavy Forward in the hand and to found a way to SS one Earth Machine on the field. I will assume here that I have already that Eart Machine monster on the field and will perform from there. I will give after that ways to access this monster.

- Normal Summon Harvester and activate its effect to add Road Roller to the hand.

- Link Summon the Ballista using Harvester and the Earth Machin already on the field.

- Activate Ballista effect to add Box and then Box effect to add Infinitrack Crab Crane to the hand.

- Activate Crane effect tributing Ballista to SS Crane.

- Activate Cran effect banishing Ballista to add Outrigger to the hand.

- The effect of Road trigger in the hand to SS itself.

- Activate Outrigger from the hand, portecting your Xyz from targeting.

- Summon Infinitrack River Stormer and then activate its effect detaching Crane to add whatever you want from hand. Usually the targets are either Superheavy Samurai Motorbike if you didn't use the SHS engine yet, or, if you already use it, a card for the follow-up like Pegasus or Anchor Drill. You can also send Trencher or Tunneler to the GY instead. Trencher allow to extend and Tunneler to draw.

- Activate Outrigger effect targeting River to SS Arise-Heart. You now have an Arise protected from targets and that is quite hard to pass through battle because of Road Roller's effect.

 

How to acces the Earth Machine monster ? Now to perform the previous combo you need one Earth Machine monster on the field. There is 3 ways to do it : Infinitrack Anchor Drill , Vernusylph of the Awakening Forests or the SHS engine. Those are my favorite but you can use other instead, like the trains. I found those quite usefull since Anchor is accessible through Heavy Forward, the Vernusylph can send a Road Roller to the GY to SS after and the SHS engine is so powerfull here.

 

The SHS combo : I come now to the SHS engine and all the versatility it gives to the deck. I recall here the basic SHS combo :

- Wakaushi -> Monk -> Soulgaia

You now have 2 LV4 on the field. One of them being an Earth Machine tuner. What can you do from there ?

- You can perform your previous combo, Soulgaia being the Earth Machine monster.

- You can Xyz Summon Gear Gigant X to add Harvester turning your SHS engine on a one card combor. You can also add something else to extend like another infinitrack.

- You can go into the Synchrol line. Synchro Bureido and activate its effect to SS Shirokunishi and place Wakaushi into the Pendulum zone. Synchro Bureibu and activate its effect to SS Kunamzan.

This last play is the most powerfull. The Kunamzan can be used as the Earth Machine monster from Infinitrack combo but it also provide a LV5 to go into Cyber Dragon Infinity. It also provide a Pendulum Summon that can help to extend either with Pegasus or Anchor Drill and can often give access to Infinity or S:P.

deck_excerpt: Crow Hogan's deck updated. Trying to bring the best out of his character deck whilst keeping it in the ARC-V era.
deck_description:
Blackwing Assault - Crow Hogan's deck updated. Trying to bring the best out of his character deck whilst keeping it in the ARC-V era so no Link monsters.

Let me know if you've got any ideas to improve it.

(This is a modified version of my original profile, which can be seen at https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/abc-xyz-ft-the-world-turbo-524971)

After a lot of testing and theorycrafting, I've been able to modify my original build into a much higher power ceiling, increasing its ability to build a heavily defensive board and enhance its grind game in the situations where you cannot perform the cheeky The World FTK without sacrificing the capability to perform said FTK. I even made a (terrible) video showing how this time!

First things first, the ability to perform The World FTK is a 1-card combo off of both Union Hangar (which includes Terraforming and Set Rotation) and Union Activation. The line is similar within both, as your goal is just to gather all six pieces of the A-to-Z fusions, get Light Barrier, and put Union Activation into the GY. Basically, this hasn't changed from the previous build.

A major change, however, is the expansion of the Fiendsmith engine to be more complete. The addition of Lacrima and Sanct in addition to Engraver is just to give the deck a bit more grind capability - you can summon Lacrima off of Requiem to pitch Engraver for the summon of Desirae and link Desirae and Sequence off for Agnumdei, and that will set you up for at least one revival of Desirae if it's outed at some point. Of course, this is all in the event you either decide you dont want to or are unable to position yourself to summon The World.

Speaking of "unable to summon The World", the backup endboard has been modified greatly, weaving both Psy-Framelord Omega and Silhouhatte Rabbit into the line to add both a hand rip and a summon negate in the form of Azurune.

All in all, these modifications make the deck feel much nicer - less chaff in the Extra Deck, every piece of the combo is actually used reasonably often, and the ability to FTK is not sacrificed in the process.

deck_excerpt: It is December 2024, and Runick remains the strongest Spright variant in Masterduel!
deck_description:
It is December 2024, nearly two years after Spright has been released, and Runick remains the strongest Spright variant in Masterduel! Don't believe me? Watch the video and play it for yourself!

The ridiculously strong combination of Spright and Runick's smothering control and endless grind game create a deck that all strategies would have to fear and respect. Sprights ending on 3-5 interruptions (Red's monster negate, Carrot's S/T negate, Smasher's banish, and I:P Masquerena's quick link) combined with Runick's draw 3 and quick play spells generally stop any deck cold in their tracks. Both archetypes combined have a potential 10+ interruptions for your opponent to slog through, while maintaining a superior resource loop - outpacing most other strategies!

If you want a detailed guide on how to pilot this deck, check out my article from a last year.

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_name: Yami Marik: Paleozoic / Winged Dragon of Ra (LOTD:LE)
deck_description:
This deck was made based on Winged Dragon of Ra, the Egyptian god.

This card's first owner was Marik Ishtar, a gravekeeper of Pharaoh's tomb whose was sucked by the darkness of the Millennium Rod, turning him into Yami Marik the "Rare Hunter".

As you know Legacy of the Duelist Link Evolution doesn't have the great support of Divine-Beasts nor the Ra itself. But Ra is an even stronger GOD than the other 2, because of the Sphere Mode.

In this deck you can make use of Sphere Mode but you can summon Ra even with normal tributing. There are many cards that let you summon multiple monsters while there are many cards to control the board with the help of paleozoics. "The first Monarch" can be treated as 2 monsters when tributed, to make the summoning easier. Most paleozoic decks exceed the 40 cards limit for consistency (to 60 cards main deck) by adding "Needlebug nest" and many other useless paleozoics. But this isn't just a Paleozoic deck, it's made for summoning Ra and we don't want to discard Ra cards randomly...

The idea came from the card "Metal Reflect Slime" which is a trap card treated as a monster. While "Mother Grizzly" can search "Deep Diver", which is able to search for every possible monster card, something that is so difficult for other cards (cause Ra and Slifer doesn't have ATK, they have ???? or even XXXX).

"Shining angel" can search for "Junk collector" and if you have "elemental burst" in grave you can wype the opponent's board.

You don't have to use Extra Deck cards that much, but these might be good in crucial moments and situations. In the side deck you can find even more good options that can work with the main deck if you want to try and build something better. I hope you liked it!
Main wincon is Rank 8 with Draglubion, with Gren Maju being a backup plan.

deck_excerpt: Domain Format: Budget Structure Deck Power-Ups
deck_description:
We're going to pop-pop-pop 'till we can't no more! 

This is a Domain Format list built upon a $11.99 purchase of the Structure Deck: Fire Kings. This will be a $10 upgrade consisting of cards purchased from sites like TCGplayer. 

Deckmaster: Crusadia Reclusia 
Domain Restrictions: FIRE / SPELLCASTER / CRUSADIA
Made for Domain Format: Join the Community Discord!

To create this upgrade, please remove these 15 cards from the SD: Fire Kings (in the sidedeck): 

  • ydke://QyWQBdgxXwEfqvUDtWTlAKyGqQMQjCYAE/00A2YlHAEi3xwEnCbOBTe5UQKx6sEFAK9nBf2JnAV6feQDcDZuA+OwKgPwlJoFONleAckOdgSEqkUCxTGKA3xJdwU8fZ4D+wR4AsEFUAKlTI8C+5oxAw==!bFjTA1YT1QGw3ugC!YzrEBalj9QNs2S4BIWoABMQAkQOdljgDwYheBP3sNQAF4zQDlVXOAF2xBQBhVmcD9esBBH8OEwAiSJkA!
  • https://ygoprodeck.com/pack/Structure%20Deck%3A%20Fire%20Kings/

Next, you will want to buy and add these cards to the deck: 

  • ydke://Tn8RBZ87JwRAAL8DvmF7AGWuwwFWdAkDDcWFBUgpmANYaEsDS/iKAIH8PwOpu6sBRfAuBWBpdgX1kzYFLfv+BNnChACJVxECgku5BQ31DAFudx0ExanaBJAGIwBEGfAACvc7A/32RAOVA4wAWXtjBN3RdwCnN4gBQKXzAKJPigA=!At+pADtpwAPdP+8DcU0qAEkllgBMa9gDlc48BYIDQgLTwNgCTMKSAJcdTgSNJ5gD!ietKAw==!

Notably, this deck does not use Infinite Impermanence which is currently a pricy card at $7. You may choose to add it into the deck or sell it to fund the $10 purchase of cards you'll need. 

Additional Resources can be found here: https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1c8_W7TLHoExz9Iq2yNBKG4kniKN3fjamfMVRehPRitQ/edit?usp=sharing

Domain Format General Rules:

  • Singleton Format: Every card restricted to 1 copy per deck.
  • 60-card Format: Each Main Deck must contain exactly 60 cards.
  • 4-player Pods: Each player competes individually in an all-out battle against three opponents.
  • Deckmaster Restrictions: Each player chooses a "Deckmaster" which dictates the allowed types and attributes for their deck.
  • Deckmaster Contract: A Deckmaster can be summoned from a designated "Deckmaster Zone" using normal summoning rules. After switching zones, Deckmasters may return to the "Deckmaster Zone," where they start the game.

Refer here for additional rules and exceptions:

https://www.domainformat.com/rules 

Broad Categories

This simple strategy has cards that fall into 3 broad categories:

  • Big Monsters
  • Self-Revivers
  • Poppers

The Big Monsters:

- Beat over your opponents!
- Summons themselves from the Hand!

This categaory of monsters includes Dogmatika Fleurdelis, the Knighted , The Blazing Mars , and Burning Dragon in order to keep ourselves with a healthy board with monsters that are easy to summon from hand with their own effects. These monsters do also have effects that trigger and give us benefits. 

Cards like Spell Card "Soul Exchange" and Trade-In are included to derive additional benefits from these cards. 

The Self-Revivers

- Be sticky and hard to Boardwipe!
- Have no fear of being destroyed and sent to the GY!
- Always have material to access the Extra Deck with! 

Monsters such as Promethean Princess, Bestower of Flames and Sacred Fire King Garunix are vital to our strategy by easily reviving themselves from the graveyard and providing benefits on summon. Our goal every game to to access these two as soon as possible. 

Promethean Princess, Bestower of Flames interacts with our opponent on their turn by reviving hereself and removing one of their monsters, and on our own turn allows us to revive one of our monsters in the GY, which can trigger additional effects. 

Sacred Fire King Garunix can revive from GY and then can destroy a monster in our deck, most cases destroying cards like Fencing Fire Ferret which will then allow us to interact with our opponent. 

Combined, these sticky monsters allow us to have plays every turn of the game and be resiliant to boardwipes. 

To find Sacred Fire King Garunix we use Foolish Burial and Fire King Island with its searchers.

To summon the Link-3 Promethean Princess, Bestower of Flames we use extenders such as Crusadia Arboria and our deckmaster Crusadia Reclusia 

Poppers

- Interact with our Opponent! 
- Remove their hopes and dreams!

The primary method this deck interacts is through popping cards using the deckmaster Crusadia Reclusia. Addtionally, Sacred Fire King Garunix will allow us to access other cards which destroy cards when they themselves are destroyed such as Fire King High Avatar Garunix and Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys 

We do not care ourselves if our monsters are destroyed, so we use cards such as Dark Hole, Supply Squad, and Ebon Sun to benefit from this aspect of the deck. 

What do we want our deckmaster to do?  Crusadia Reclusia 

- Free Extender! 
- Triggers Sacred Fire King Garunix!
- Reliable, Reuseable popping!
- Crusadia OTK!

The Crusadia Reclusia we choose as deckmaster has an inherent summon and a reliable pop of an opponent's card when we want it. Notably, this can destroy either a spell/trap or a monster, providing great flexiblity. 

 Additionally, it can provide access to the Crusadia Engine, a combo that puts out Crusadia Regulex with backup from Crusadia Revival to attack all monsters on the field with a amplified attack stat. This combo starts from normal summoning Crusadia Reclusia to link into Crusadia Magius then summoning Crusadia Reclusia using its own inherent summoning.  

To captilize on the popping effect, we use cards such as Enemy Controller to tribute Crusadia Reclusia before its own effect destroys it. Remember that the popping is optional, and we may choose to use Crusadia Reclusia as a simple extender to access our other Extra Deck Link Monsters. 

To recap:

Important Cards: Sacred Fire King Garunix , Promethean Princess, Bestower of Flames , Supply Squad , Crusadia Reclusia 

Strategy Elevator Pitch: Pop all their stuff, then beat them up with high-level, high-attack monsters. 

Suggested Alternatives:

 Diabellstar the Black Witch + Original Sinful Spoils - Snake-Eye + Susurrus of the Sinful Spoils , Battlin' Boxer Uppercutter , Salamangreat Gazelle + Salamangreat Miragestallio , Dogmatika Nexus , Infernoble Knight Captain Oliver , Fighting Flame Swordsman , Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians , Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax , Magical Dimension , Snake-Eye Ash , Magmacho Dragon , Ancient Warriors - Ambitious Cao De , Brushfire Knight , Successor Soul , The Winged Dragon of Ra - Sphere Mode , Lava Golem , Volcanic Queen , Gold Pride - Nytro Head 

Please remember, the most important goal is to have fun!

deck_name: World Chalice - Spright and Diabellstar Engine
deck_description:
After the release of Ib (the World Chalice Justiciar), World Chalice has potential again.
It's relativiely simple in this build, no room for non-engine, but what we can run a total of 14 ways to get to out main starter, T.G. Rocket Salamander.
The base combo is this-
Summon Rocket Salamander (through any means, Normal summon, special summon through OSS or One for One, ect) > Tribute Salamander for it's effect, summon Screw Serpent, Serpent revive Salamander, Synchro into Ib, Ib effect add World Legacy World Chalice.
If you special summoned Salamander, you're fine to just normal summon the Chalice by tributing Ib. If you normal summoned Salamander, you'll need to summon Ib the the EMZ, and then link it off for Gravity Controller (after which you use Ib effect summon Crowned, link Crowned into Imduk, Tribute Controller and summon Chalice. then resume combo)
After summoning Chalice, use Ib's effect to summon Lee from deck, then Lee effect to add Crowned. Link Lee and Chalice into something (Currently testing Sprind, but Auram should work as well. This list was originally a Master Duel deck and I used Spright Elf, but that's banned in the TCG) then Chalice effect summon Guardragon and Crowned from deck. Next is where it changes up a bit, I know there's a lot you can do from this point but currently what I've found to work best is to XYZ into Gigantic and do Spright plays.
Currently Rocket Salamander (special summoned) gets me to Gigantic, S:P, Abomination, and Avramax OR Avramax (made with I:P), Earlie, Gigantic, and a set Sorrows
Originally in Master Duel, I would end on Apollousa instead of Abomination (Abomination is just a replacement with good arrows and an okay effect, I could see Saryuja Skull Dread being a good option as well)

deck_description:
ryzeal

How to play (step by step)

combo 1

1) normal summon ice ryzeal, activate effect to search sword ryzeal from deck

2) summon sword, activate effect and search ext ryzeal

3) summon out ext ryzeal by disgarding a xyz monster to the GY (preferably detonator), add node ryzeal from deck to hand

4) overlay sword and ext to make duodrive

5) activate duodrive effect to add whatever xyz monster you sent in the GY earlier as material

6) detach two to search plugin and ryzeal cross from deck to hand

7) activate ryzeal cross, special summon node ryzeal, activate effect to bring back a ryzeal monster from the GY to the field (i would choose ext)

8) over lay node and ext to make bagooska

9) activate plugin from hand, bring back sword and attach a ryzeal card (preferably hole thruster) to duodrive

10) overlay ice and sword to make detonator

deck_description: the extra deck needs to be 15 cards just put some randoms in there

My pure Destiny HERO deck. The goal is to use Dreadmaster for the fusion of either DPE or Dominance. Once it's your opponent's turn you can pop Dominance and their card to bring out Dreadmaster for the protection and then of course the big punch next turn. That's really it, just big guy punch. It's fun. The D-Force in the side deck is if you're going second and need to turbo out Plasma. The D-Tactics are for Dystopia, which is why I have a second one in the side deck. D-Tactics is a lot more gimmicky than the Dominance line so unless you're messing around I wouldn't really go for it. Since it's a pure Destiny HERO deck I tried to use as little of the other HERO cards as possible, hence the "weird" ratio of Vision and Elemental HEROs. I've been building and updating this deck for months now and this is what's been working best for me. Feel free to ask or tell me improvements in the comments.

deck_excerpt: Duel-Ignition Deck: Swordsoul is a set in the Asian-English Yu-Gi-Oh! Official Card Game (OCG).
deck_description: Duel-Ignition Deck: Swordsoul is a set in the Asian-English Yu-Gi-Oh! Official Card Game (OCG).

At last, a meaningful meta change is upon us.  Ryzeal is expected to be the best deck, and Maliss is a contender, if not the favorite, for the #2 spot.  Dormouse and White Rabbit both represent full combo, and Mining makes them more accessible.  The formerly bulk common TCGE Haggard Lizardose has become a key part of this deck to turn Dormouse or White Rabbit into Red Ransom without using Splash mage immediately and getting Cyberse locked, additionally letting you hold TB 11 for later in Dormouse starts so it can be used to banish Ransom to get Dotscaper into rotation.  Neo-Tempest Terahertz and base (post errata) Firewall are key pieces in the deck, something that has been a long time coming for both.

 

With 9 cards representing full combo without anything else specific this deck is around 75% to open one and has 21 non-engine slots, 19 hand traps (including 4 bystials who also serve as extenders if you aren't cyberse locked by Splash Mage and Transcode), called by, and Gold Sarc which is, admittedly, functionally engine, but not combo on its own.  Packbit, Desavewurm, Aggregator and Code of Soul are your sends for Terahertz, each providing different utility.  Packbit is non-destruction removal, Aggregator is a negate of a faceup card, Desavewurm is always being sent t1 so you can banish it as a Spell/Trap Negate, and Code of Soul functions as a pseudo I:P from grave.  Otherwise the ED is the Maliss links which serve as Extention and interaction and a Bunch of the Cyberse usual suspects.

 

Shifter is in the side since it does have consequences on your end board and does very little to Ryzeal, Lancea is good in the mirror and also helps into something like Voiceless that is expected to see a bump with the Ryu-ge Ritual giving the deck a searchable D-Fissure than is online on the opponents turn only, by stopping Saffira's Ritual summon effect.  Thrust for Ultimate Slayer as removal and a way to exploit the Terahertz package further, and D-Barrier is one of the strongest cards in the game going first.  Crossout is a common side in, especially since crossout on Shifter or Lancea is a definite benefit, along with the Nibiru and the main deck stuff like Fuwalos.

 

No Impulse for a couple reasons, A its still $60 a pop and it conflicts with a lot of your extenders like Dotscaper, Transcode and Firewall, while clashing with a number of the Hand Traps in the deck like Veiler, Mourner and Fuwalos, and not actually being that high impact into the expected meta.  Remember, about half the cost of the deck is Fuwalos, so if you replace it and ideally have the Druiswurms in hand the cost ends up being not that bad.  I'll be posting an updated VV list soon, but otherwise this is it.

Ritual decks are never particularly good, but I did my best with this. The whole idea of Nouvelles is that your opponent never wants to target anything ever, or you can climb up the ritual levels. this best can put up a ton of interruption with very few cards on field, with my end board usually being, at the worst, just buerillabaisse and chef's special recipe. however if the opportunity presents itself, diviner, who is already a good combo piece, can be used to synchro summon after sending arc light to grave. I find it easiest to put up level 7 (diviner + poissonaire/buerillabaisse) or level 12 (Diviner + baelgril/hungry burger) however most levels are doable to some extent, if you want to substitute in a different synchro. Vagnawa is in the side deck as a time card when nessesary as this deck cannot burn in any other way. only other things to note is that benten can search itself on a non-once per turn when tributed for ritual material, while also searching diviner or trias. diviner and poissonaire both have important effects on summon, but also when tributed effect, which makes trias and enemy controller(going second) incredibly helpful to get around targeting negates (veiler/imperm/etc).
Overall deck works out most of the time, but in the case where you only get 1 starter and the opponent has ash, it's so over.

deck_excerpt: Cyber Dragon Tactics Mk 2.01 is based on the Cyber Dragon Tactical Try Deck for the OCG based around OTK strategies

deck_description:
This is a fusion-heavy deck using "Dragon Master Magia" and "Red Eyes Dark Dragoon" as the primary boss monsters.

Plan A: "Fusion Armament" is meant to set up "Blue-Eyes Ultimate Dragon" as fusion material for "Dragon Master Magia". Use "Magician of Chaos" or "Illusion of Chaos" as materials, whilst using "Ultimate Fusion".

Plan B: Use "Fusion Deployment" to summon "Dark Magician" / "Dark Magician Girl" / "Red Eyes Black Dragon" to help set them up to summon other boss fusion monsters

Plan C: Use "Magician's Rod" to search for "Dark Magical Circle"/"Soul Servant"/"Magician's Salvation"/"Eternal Soul"/"Secrets of Dark Magic". The former 4 are also searchers too. Though "Dark Magical Circle" can also banish cards when "Dark Magician" is summoned.

Plan D: Use "Magician's Soul" / "Eternal Soul" to summon "Dark Magician"

Plan E: Use "Eye of Timaeus" to summon more niche "Dark Magician" fusions like "Dark Paladin" and "Dark Cavalry" on top of regular "Dark Magician" fusions

Plan F: Link summon "Spirit with Eyes of Blue" using "Magician's Soul"/"Magician's Rod" to create dragon-type fusion materials to summon "Red Eyes Dark Dragoon"/"Amulet Dragon"/"Dark Magician the Dragon Knight"/"Dark Magician Girl the Dragon Knight"

deck_excerpt: How do you ignore half the hand traps in the game? By half your stuff happening in the grave...
deck_description:
This is a Tearlaments deck at its core that synergizes with 4 major engines, Fiendsmith, Kashtira, Horus and Shaddoll. Each engine does its thing when in the hand or in the GY.

Fiendsmith can serve independently on its own with engraver as its starter, or if you happen to have extra bodies laying around, can be made with closed goddess with 2 extra bodies from either the Horus line or other incidental summons from Tearlaments/Kashtira.

The Kashtira line is the all around last resort that stays the lowest to the ground - fenrir banish and unicorn to hose out the extra deck is very important.

The Horus line provides extra bodies needed to either go into fiendsmith line or double up as extra bodies for The Zombie Vampire for extra mills or even to go into sprind to dump Merli and fuse on the fly. Worst case scenario, they are huge beatsticks that perform non targetting send to the GY, shuffling your banished cards back and provide lots of grind in battle.

At last but not least, Shaddoll. The Shaddoll package serves as the tippy-tip of the gameplan as it is the most incidental of all of the archetypes. It's serves as a way to fuse into Shaddoll Winda to force interaction or completely win games on its own or when it's sided, serves as additional negates with Apkalone coming out easily as a summon going 2nd and providing your team with the ability to proceed forward. Shaddoll Dragon serves to destroy annoying spells and traps and floodgates on the field and Ariel banishes opponent's cards, especially good against GY needers like Fire King and Snake Eyes. Maliss/Ryzeal are very resiliant to these cards so not fully recommended to bring Ariel into most matchups.

Rainbow Bridge of Salvation is one of the few ways you are able to bridge the 3 archetypes with field spells together - Horus, Tearlaments and Kashtira. Use this to grab whatever field spell is needed. You are, however running a garnet in Crystal Beast Emerald Tortoise which serves no purpose in this deck other to enable the Salvation when it is in the GY.

Mill well and have an opening hand that can shoot out all 4 lines. Play low with Kash and swing hard with everyone else.

deck_name: Armageddon / Impcantation cheap deck for MasterDuel
deck_description:
This is a very cheap deck which can be used for every ritual archetype. The basic idea was to summon the OG Demise ritual monster to break the field and then with the help of the level 10 Ruin ritual card (which can attack 2 times in a row if summoned correctly) to attack with these 2 cards for game.

But this restrictions makes this strategy a bit of impossible. So my next approach was to bring the OG Demise ritual monster and then the Impcantation boss monster with 2 other Impcantation monsters to hit for 9400 LP. 

This might not be that easy to make a first turn kill cause handtraps and other disruptions can slow the process. This deck contains a 9 card draw engine which can help a lot with cycling through materials and pieces of the combo.

Impcantation Ratios: Most of the times Ritual monsters are way more accessible, cause we use more of them. The main reason for that is that Impcantation ritual spell can be retrieved from grave. So it's smarter to use more of level 3 and level 6 Impcantation monsters to activate them from hand. The level 10 Boss monster can even suffle them back to deck if needed, to never run out of resources.

Cards like swords of concealing light and gravity bind can help with slowing down your opponent, while they can be targets for Magician's soul or can even be destroyed by Demise.

deck_description: White Forest Toys For Master Duel Post Selection Pack: Chaotic Showtime

my white forest centur-ion deck

How to play (1 card combo starter)

this step by step combo starts with astellar in your starting hand

1) normal summon astellar, activate effect to disgard any spell/trap and add silvy from deck to field

2) activate silvy to search tales of the white forest from deck to hand

3) synchro silvy and astellar into rceila, activate effect to disgard tales and search woes to hand

4) activate GY effect for tales and astellar, chain link 1 tales chain link 2 astellar, astellar then summons back itself while tales gets set face down on res

5) activate tales to search elzette and syncho into diabell queen of the white forest

6) activate diabell effect to add back tales from GY, activate elzette effect to disgard tales and special summon it and to search rucia

7) special summon rucia from hand, activate effect to disgard woes and draw 1, activate woes from GY to set back onto field

8) synchro into auxilia using diabell and rucia, activate effect to search stand up centur-ion

9) activate stand up to disgard any card and place trudea in your S/T zone, activate effect to summon itself on to field

10) use trudea's effect again to place it back into S/T zone to search primera into s/t zone

11) activate primera to summon itself on to the field and search for wake up centur-ion, activate to summon a lv 8 token

12) synchro into crimson dragon using token and primera, activate crimson's effect to add synchro rumble to hand

13) activate crimson dragon's effect again, target auxlia to bring out cosmic blazar

14) link into silhouette using elzette and auxlia, activate effect to set angel statue from deck to field

15) special summon both white forest monsters from GY by returning both white forest synchro monsters to extra deck

16) link both into i:p, activate wake up in GY, send phalynx from deck to GY, use its GY effect to bring back auxlia

17) activate synchro rumble to bring back any 1 of 2 white forest monsters to field

18) end phase, auxlia places primera in s/t zone

*end board should have total of 7-8 disruptions
Use Blaster, Dragon Ruler of Infernos and Burner, Dragon Ruler of Sparks to get to your engine and clean up with extra copies of Sangen Kaimen, Tenpai Dragon Chundra, and Sangen Summoning.

A very stupid, semi bricky, but surprisingly synergistic deck, all to make a dumb pun with a royal Knightmare Goblin I got in my first 10 pull (not kidding).

Basic combo:

Make Gabonga 

Torpedo, rank up to lancer, make sure to get full armored.

If you didn't draw Orcust Knightmare, get 2 mats on field and do Orcust combo, discarding full armored.  If you have two extra materials on field, also make ip before the cymbal revive.

If you drew into Orcust Knightmare, get 2 3s, set full armored.

Ideal endboard:

Gabonga, longirsu, dingirsu, ip, lancer, orcustrated Babel/crescendo, armored XYZ in grave.

deck_name: A Beginner's Guide to White Forest (December 2024) (Masteduel)
deck_excerpt: White Forest can surprisingly summon iconic boss monsters like Dragoon, Baronne and Dis Pater!
deck_description:
White Forest has finally been release in Masterduel, and it is the Diabellstar lore's synchro spam strategy! These White Forest ladies mean business, since they make synchro plays ridiculously easy whenever and wherever they are played. The amount of card advantage the deck generates with its supporting archetypes outpace most decks of the format in a prolonged grindgame, easily winning duels with a myriad of synchro-based interruptions.
 
Rciela turns enables a search for any White Forest card for a low cost of a spell/trap discard, further fueling enabling your plays, especially when paired up with the Toy box cards. Silvera acts as a quick-play "book of the eclipse" setting facedown your opponent's entire field. Finally, Diabell recovers ANY spell/trap from the GY, while enabling a quick synchro during your opponent's turn! All these ladies are enabled with a compact but potent engine of 14 White Forest cards!
 
Diabellstar's "synchro" archetype certainly shows a lot of promise as a synchro engine - especially when it's paired up with the Toy Box engine and Bystials. 
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
White Forest is actually made up of three different archetypes, but somehow still a ton of staples! 

The WHITE FOREST section of the strategy are synchro-enablers, allowing the pilot to summon multiple synchro boss monsters to the field. White Forest cards also synergize very well with spell cards, since they use them as cost to enable them to spam tuners and synchro material on the field. The starters are 3 Astellar, 3 Elzette and 3 Silvy - all searchers and summoners from deck. 3 Rucia isn't a starter, but it is a valuable extender since she summons from hand. 1 Tales of the White Forest (searcher), and 1 Woes of the White Forest (interruption) are used since they all reset themselves on the field when they are sent to the GY as cost for a monster effect, and are combo pieces for the strategy.
 
A TOY BOX engine is used to further fuel the White Forest portion of the deck. Toy Box and Toy Soldier search each other, and Toy Box sets two cards from deck - giving White Forest plenty of spells to send to the GY as cost. It's not even a "hard" once per turn, so if you have multiple Toy Boxes you can keep setting resources from deck! The Toy Box monsters also summon themselves to the field whenever they're sent to the GY, so it gives additional bodies for synchro summons. Finally, Toy Box has a surprise battle phase effect to destroy attacking monsters by sending a set card to the GY, offering further defensive play. It is composed of 3 Toy Box, 3 Toy Soldier and 1 Toy Tank. 
 
The BYSTIAL engine works extremely well with the White Forest strategy, granting the deck level 6 and 8 bodies to synchro summon with. Since White Forest is a light deck, it also synergizes very well with the interactions Bystials offer. For example, Dis Pater can summon your banished White Forest cards from the banished pile so you can continue comboing, and Branded Regained can recycle spent light/dark monsters in your GY so you can summon them again. On top of that, Bystials counter a fairly big number of today's meta like Gimmick Puppet, Yubel and Tearlaments. 
 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
White Forest interrupts your opponent with Silvera's fieldwide "Book of Eclipse," Baronne's negate, Dragoon's negate and Diabell's quick-synchro into Chaos Angel's banish.
 
White Forest combos are somewhat linear, but resilient and can weave through interruption. They consist of climbing to Synchro 6s -> 8s -> 10s and potentially 12s as the combo goes on. Depending on your hand, White Forest duelists end on a mix of Chengying (banish), Dis Pater/Dragoon (negate + destroy), Diabelle (quick synchro), Silvera (set opponent's entire field) and several handtraps in hand due to draws and searches. These boards are generally enough to stop an opponent's turn and outresource them with White Woods! 
 
Here is the optimal opening combo for White Forest: 
 
Astellar + Toy Box = Diabell (summon from Extra Deck Zapper Shrimp which pops 1 spell/trap) + Chaos Angel (targeted banish, summoned with Zapper Shrimp and Diabell) + Dragoon (omni-negate/destroy), + Woes of the White Forest (summons Silvera which sets all monsters your opponent controls face-down) + 1 draw + follow-up for next turn. 
  1. Activate Toy Box. Activate Toy's effect to set from deck Toy Tank and Toy Soldier. 
  2. Normal summon Astellar. 
  3. Activate Astellar's effect to send to GY Toy Soldier and summon from deck Silvy. 
  4. CL1 activate Silvy's effect to search for Tales of the White Forest and CL2 Toy Soldier's effect in the GY to summon itself. 
  5. Activate Toy Soldier's on-summon effect to search for Rucia. 
  6. Special summon Rucia from hand (since you control a White Forest monster). 
  7. Activate Rucia's effect send to GY Toy Tank to draw 1 card. 
  8. Activate Toy Tank's effect in the GY to summon itself.
  9. Synchro summon Rciela using Astellar + Rucia. 
  10. Activate Rciela's on-summon effect sending Tales of the White Forest to GY to search for Woes of the White Forest from deck. 
  11. CL1 activate Astellar's GY effect to summon herself, CL2 activate Tales of the White Forest's effect in the GY to set itself on the field. 
  12. Activate Tales of the White Forest to search from deck Elzette. 
  13. Synchro summon Diabell using Astellar + Rciela. 
  14. Activate Diabell's on-summon effect to recover Tales of the White Forest from the GY. 
  15. Activate Elzette's effect to summon herself from hand and add any White Forest monster from deck (follow-up for next turn), sending from hand Woes of the White Forest.
  16. Activate Woes of the White Forest's effect in the GY to set itself on the field. 
  17. Synchro summon Muddy Mudragon using Elzette + Silvy.
  18. Activate Mudragon's effect to fusion summon Albion the Branded Dragon using itself + Toy Tank. 
  19. Activate Albion's on-summon effect to fuse itself and Mudragon in the GY to fusion summon Dragoon. 
  20. During your opponent's turn, you can summon from the GY Silvy by returning Rciela to the Extra Deck. CL1 Elzette's effect to add herself from GY to hand, CL2 Silvy's effect to search to chainblock (but it'll be negated). 
  21. During your opponent's turn, you can activate Woes of the White Forest to summon a level 2 White Forest monster from deck and synchro summon with it + Silvy for Silvera to flip all of your opponent's monsters facedown. 
  22. During your opponent's turn, you can activate Diabell's effect sending Tales of the White Forest to summon from Extra Deck Zapper Shrimp! CL1 Zapper Shrimp to destroy a spell/trap your opponent controls, CL2 Tales of the White Forest to set itself on the field. Then you can synchro summon Chaos Angel using Zapper Shrimp + Diabell for a targeted banish and to protect your synchro monsters. 
Many combinations of two cards more or less make the same endboards, and you can customize the monsters that you summon specifically to the match-up. 

For your follow-up next turn, your incredible resource engines (Bystial/Toy Box) and White Forest recursion should allow you to out-resource your opponent! 
 
Going first, you make an unbreakable board with multilayered interruption and with plenty of follow-up next turn.
 
Going second, you weaken your opponent with the 16 handtraps/staples you have. Then your engines should bait enough interruption and generate enough resources and beatsticks to push through your opponent's board!
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • To break your opponent's board as you go through your synchro combo, summon Silvera (sets every monster of your opponent's facedown), Coral Dragon (destroy 1), Baronne (banish), and S:P Little Knight (banish). Also, you have the option of using Silvera's double piercing damage effect she gives to every Spellcaster and Illusion synchro for an OTK!
  • Duelist's don't read toy box's defensive attack declaration effect to destroy the attacking monster. Use it to your advantage to hardcounter battlephase oriented decks like Tenpai! Alot of players insta-leave when the effect resolves!
  • The Toy Box engine represents 3 separate pieces of material you get to use for White Forest's send fodder, as well as additional bodies on board for your Synchro, XYZ, Link and Fusion summons! Toy Box also isn't a hard once per turn, so if you have another copy, you can set more resources from deck!
  • If you have full combo (for ex. Astellar + Toy Box), try to go through your White Forest combo first, then go for Dragoon or whatever other synchro boss monster afterward. That way, if you get Nibiru'd you can still keep extending with your White Forest Synchro and level 4 White Forest lady in the GY. 
  • If you get Maxx C'd, Shifter'd, Droll'd or get hit some other lingering floodgate and can't extend anymore, make Bagooska to stall until your next turn so you can try comboing again. 
  • Bystial Dis Pater and the Bystial engine can recycle and resummon your banished Light/Dark monsters! Try to access Dis Pater as soon as possible since he does so much for the deck!
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
      The synchro archtype of the Diabellstar storyline certainly doesn't disappoint! White Forest can pump out very competent synchro-centric boards with threats like Dis Pater, Chaos Angel and Baronne! The rare ability to field a fusion powerhouse like Dragoon and an XYZ staple like Abyss Dweller is an amazing boon for this strategy as well! It's resilience through handtraps, it's flexibility in any gamestate, and its sheer power as a combo juggernaut has earned White Forest a place in the highly competitive metagame dominated by the likes of Yubel, Snake-Eyes and Tenpai.
 
 Don't underestimate these mysterious sorcerers from the forest, or else you'll be blasted away by their myriad of interruptions and sheer card advantage! Will this promising new archetype, White Forest have metagame relevance just like it's lore centric brethren such as Snake-Eye, Tearlaments or Branded? Only time will time! 
 
GLHF Duelists!

This is a blind second sky striker deck. Important concept: This is a sky striker deck, not a tenpai deck, in which tenpai is used as bait to set up spells in the gy, material for the otk line and potenially otk just as how they are designed to, do not afraid to use desire but be careful with it. This deck works well aginst ryzeal, blue eyes, or potenally all fusion/link deck unless under shifter. The main play for this deck is to ultilize ultimate slayer to bounce and send back to extra deck for a free plus 1, while using spell cards to either bait negates and/or to filter out ultimate slayer. This deck frequently uses the link otk line to bait out opponent's interruptions while setting up small board with the effect of princess, then if possible set up negates to later drain down resources. Given chances tenpai's small trident dragion line would be useful for otking too. Super poly is currently an interesting board breaker in the format: Everything is fusable in Maliss's board, while detonator could be used as fusion material given that you start with the striker engine(most of the time)[Ignition Beast Volcannon = Machine + Pyro], they could also be used as the target for the sky striker field spell if they became a brick. The play is likely used as a bait for detonator's pop and could trigger and summon raye from the deck. Facing Maliss match ups, it is recommanded to bring chaos hunter instead of lancea is to limit the impact of shifter, where it could disable the Ultimate Slayer and Dropplet along with the striker engine. The deck does suffer from maliss match due to shifter, voiceless voice due to being unable to target monster with card effects and kashtira fiendsmith since the deck cannot interact with hand and may lose to the grind game. However the main advantage of this deck is a suprise for people who thought tenpai is dead and not knowing to hit the striker line or tenpai line.

deck_excerpt: Rikka, Plants, Casual, Tribute, Beginner Friendly, Cute, Aroma, Sylvan
deck_description:
This is a Pure Rikka deck that I like to use often for casual and fun play. It is not meant to be the best or meta/competitive whatsoever but can still be used in order to be able to play somewhat decently.

Many of the handtraps can be replaced by other generic plant support such as the Aroma cards, the Ragnaraika cards, Sunavalon/Sunvine/Sunseed cards, or other generic plant support cards like -Therion "Lily" Borea, -Rose Girl, and -Evil Thorn just to name a few ideas.

The Side Deck is comprised of some generic going second cards and things the deck lacks such as backrow removal as well as two other Extra Deck cards to consider which are -Sylvan Princessprite and -Orea, the Sylvan High Arbiter.

A sample combo for this deck is as follows: 

Our starting hand will consist of a -Rikka Petal, a -Rikka Glamour, and a -Mudan the Rikka Fairy.To start, Normal Summon Petal, activate Petal add -Snowdrop the Rikka Fairy to hand. Activate Glamour tributing Petal in order to add -Rikka Princess and -Primula the Rikka Fairy. Activate Primula's effect because a monster we control got tributed in order to special summon herself. Activate Princess' effect in order to special summon herself. XYZ into -Rikka Queen Strenna. You CAN activate Strenna here in order to send Princess to the Graveyard and then add her to your hand (Or any other card like Glamour or Petal BUT Glamour will be used for Hyperyton and Petal likes to stay in the Grave). But for this example, I will keep Princess in the grave so I will NOT activate Strenna's effect. Activate Snowdrop's effect in order to tribute Strenna in order to special summon Mudan and Snowdrop. Mudan and Strenna will activate at the same time. You can choose the chain however you want and whichever you think is more important first. In this example, chain 1 will go to Mudan. Strenna, because she got tributed, will special summon a Rank 5 or higher Plant monster from the Extra Deck OR Graveyard and then attach herself as material. We will summon -Sacred Tree Beast, Hyperyton and attach Strenna as material. Mudan will add -Rikka Konkon from the Deck to the Hand. Activate Konkon and activate Hyperton's effect in order to attach Glamour from the Graveyard to itself as material (Now it has either a monster or spell negate during your opponent's turn). Activate Snowdrop's second effect in order to target herself and make all Plant monsters you currently control the same level as the targeted monster. In this instance, Mudan and Snowdrop will both be Level 8. XYZ into -Teardrop the Rikka Queen. Activate Konkon's effect in order to set -Rikka Sheet. And now, you can end your turn.

This end board consists of a Quick Effect Tribute (Teardrop), a monster/spell negate (Hyperyton), a monster negate as long as you control a Rikka monster (Princess in Hand or GY), a negate for a face-up monster (Sheet), and a tribute for the effect of either Sheet or Princess (Konkon passive effect). As well as a Petal in the GY in order to special summon during your opponent's End Phase.

The general game plan for the deck is to Normal Summon Petal, activate her effect to search out whatever Rikka monster you might need, (which for me I found is usually Snowdrop or Mudan) and then Tribute Petal using one of the Rikka monsters you added and you go from there.
The end board usually consists of: Teardrop the Rikka Queen, Sacred Tree Beast, Hyperyton with Rikka Queen Strenna and a spell card equipped as material, Rikka Konkon in the Field Spell Zone, a Rikka Princess in the Graveyard or the Hand, and a set Rikka Sheet as well as maybe a Rikka Petal in the Graveyard in order to summon during the End Phase of your opponent's turn. 

Overall, this is one of my favourite decks and archetypes to use in any sort of play and I hope you enjoyed my deck list!

This deck utilizes the Fiendsmith engine to get access to D/D/D Wave High King Caesar before going into the Maliss combo, helping Maliss play without the prospect of Nibiru, The Primal Being eating your board.

The deck sacrifices access to Firewall Dragon Darkfluid - Neo Tempest Terahertz and a large amount of the extra deck to playing good generic cyberse extra deck monsters; however, you get access to the powerful Fiendsmith engine to help play more low to the ground. This, combined with a larger than normal Bystial package, you can out grind your opponents.

Ideally, you end on D/D/D Wave High King Caesar, Maliss Q Hearts of Crypter, set Maliss C GWC-06 to summon Maliss Q White Binder from the grave to banish cards in the graveyard.Alternatively, you can end on Fiendsmith's Desirae, and using the Fiendsmith's Sequence as link material to link climb into your Maliss link monsters.

Simul Archfiend is a neat card that can counter a spread of matchups better than Dimensional Barrier, preventing your opponent from summoning links, xyz or fusion. Dimension shifter tests the current meta and may be replaced, as this deck does not synergize well with it.

All in all, Maliss is a deck that suffers heavily to cards like Artifact Lancea and Nibiru, the Primal Being. In my opinion, Firewall Dragon Darkfluid - Neo Tempest Terahertz isn't strong enough for the meta. Maliss don't really have good normal summons other than Maliss P Dormouse, so having the Maliss field spell in hand is often times better than having the Maliss monsters in hand. Fiendsmith is a strong second engine in the deck, and going second, along with the Bystials, allows you to play into a board better.

deck_excerpt: Wander the White Forest with Synchro Summons!
deck_description:
Yet another cute girl deck that I was very excited for from the moment it was revealed, White Forest is a deck in the Diabellstar lore, centering around Diabellstar (Astellar, as she was called back then) when she was a child alongside her once-friend Elzette as they grew up in the titular White Forest. It's also a very fun Synchro deck that's presently Rogue-ish in Master Duel right now. It's not perfect, but the small engine requirements and flexible build options can snatch games even against the best.

Due to laziness, I will not be doing a card-by-card, but it's got potential to be tiered when the Azamina cards come out. I don't think it's going to be top tier (outside of like a month or two if the Azamina cards release before Ryzeal/Maliss, and even then it'd probably not be a stand-out top tier), but it's got enough teeth to compete.

Beware the White Forest, for it may consume you completely (and make you into a Synchro supremacist like me).

deck_excerpt: Control Total: Neutraliza las Invocaciones Especiales con Archlord Kristya Total Control: Neutralize Special Summons with Archlord Kristya
deck_description:
Main Objective: This deck focuses on neutralizing your opponent's special summons, using the powerful Archlord Kristya as a key card.

Strategy
Archlord Kristya: This card is not only a strong attacker but also limits your opponent's special summons. Its ability lets you regain control of the game while blocking their strategies.

Celestial Knightlord Parshath: Use this card to search for Archlord Kristya directly from your deck. By summoning it, you can accelerate your plan and ensure Kristya is on the field as quickly as possible.

Game Plan:

  • Field Control: Maintain control by using cards that destroy or destabilize your opponent's resources while protecting your key cards.
  • Kristya Summon: Search for Archlord Kristya with Celestial Knightlord Parshath and place it on the field to maximize its effect.
  • Patience: From there, wait for your opponent to falter under pressure and concede.

 

With this approach, your deck becomes an effective trap that can frustrate your opponent's strategies, forcing them to surrender due to their inability to perform special summons. Good luck in your duels!

Español:

Objetivo Principal: Este mazo se centra en neutralizar las invocaciones especiales del oponente, utilizando la poderosa Archlord Kristya como carta clave.

Estrategia
Archlord Kristya: Esta carta no solo es un gran atacante, sino que también limita las invocaciones especiales del oponente. Su habilidad te permite recuperar el control del juego mientras bloqueas sus estrategias.

Celestial Knightlord Parshath: Utiliza esta carta para buscar directamente a Archlord Kristya en tu mazo. Al invocarlo, podrás acelerar tu plan y asegurarte de tener a Kristya en el campo lo más rápido posible.

Plan de Juego:

  • Control del Campo: Mantén el control utilizando cartas que destruyan o desestabilicen los recursos del oponente, mientras proteges tus cartas clave.
  • Invocación de Kristya: Busca a Archlord Kristya con Celestial Knightlord Parshath y colócala en el campo para maximizar su efecto.
  • Paciencia: A partir de ahí, espera a que tu oponente no pueda responder a la presión y se rinda.

 

Con este enfoque, tu mazo se convierte en una trampa efectiva que puede frustrar las estrategias del oponente, llevándolos a rendirse ante la imposibilidad de realizar invocaciones especiales. ¡Buena suerte en tus duelos!

I believe that the Ryu-Ge deck can be competitvely viable. There are a few one card combos that get you 2 omni-negates, a bounce, and an on board monster negate. The deck really only dies to D-Shifter and Droll & Lock Bird. It can play through just about anything else. I would add 2 Lo, prayer of the voiceless voice if I owned the copies, no need to cut anything for them, just add them to the list. The deck wants to be above 40 cards to decrease your chances of drawing your realms.

Starting with Diviner of the Herald or Lo gets you the full combo.

Lo places the barrier, adds saffira, send to add skull guardian. Banish to Ritual the skull guardian.

Lo comes back and Skull guardian adds Mistva. - one omninegate online at your 4th summon.

Scale Mistva, add the field spell and pop it. Activate field spell. Get your 3 names. Your choice of which to which zone, prefering the dino to hand in most cases. Use dino in hand to add the dino domains, shuffle the dino back in deck. Activate the dino domains. Activate the field spell to SS all 3 of your Ryu-ge non-pendulum cards. Overlay your Wyrm and Sea Serpent into varudrus. Second Omninegate.

On your opponents turn, you use Varudrus to negate something, then detach another to destroy Varudrus, this lets you tribute your Dinosaur to summon Mistva and when Varudrus is destroyed, it lets you destroy another card on the field. Mistva pop the field spell to place sea spires, giving you a bounce.

There are other variants depending on opening hand, you can add sauravis instead of one of the other rituals if you open one of them. When side boarding you can add either protos or dogoran, if you can set up your grave or need removal, though when you get to the point of activating the field spell to grab dogoran, you usually are interrupted before.

deck_excerpt: White Forest Centurion! Yu-Gi-Oh! Deck Uploaded by Star Lord
deck_description:
The White Forest Architype gives something back to Centurion that was clearly missing before: more Tuners, that can be summoned on the opponents turn!

We still have too many normal summons, so I'm thinking of scaling Astera back for more hand-traps (the deck struggles with indestructible, untargetable monsters).

The overall 'flow' of gameplay is no where near as fluid or 'all gas' as the old Visas Synchro pile, but it has a clear identity, and clear tools to respond to most situations with. Using True Awakening, Phalanx and Silvera to intuerrupt the opponent if we go first is very effective, while going second we generally depend on the power of our spells and chain-blocking. 

Why are we playing both Emeth VI and Gargoyle II? They're both just useful. Dropping Emeth into the GY with Stand Up if we draw him feels great, while Gargoyle is just one of the best targets to search for with Stand-Up.

Since the White Forest Tuners can special summon themselves on the opponents turn, we can also make use of any extra Gargoyles or Trudeas to make Level 10 Synchros, which is why Baronne is here. Tyrant Red Dragon Archfiend is another good target, but needs more materials to make, so we're running Silhouhatte Rabbit instead.

I'm considering playing more Rucia than Silvy, since we really wanna normal summon Trudea if we don't draw Stand Up. In the same vein, dropping Astellar until we get the Azamina support.

deck_excerpt: Advance with the Ancient Gear Army through the ranks of Duelist Cup!
deck_description:
My FAVOURITE archetype of ALL TIME Ancient Gear is still a force to be reckoned with in Masterduel, so I've decided to ladder up with these killer robots for this month's Duelist Cup! 

During the Duelist Cup, I found out that most opponents underestimate the sheer might of the Ancient Gear Army! They often figure out too late that under protection cards like Ancient Gear Fortress and Ancient Gear Duel, your Ancient Gear Army is INDESTRUCTIBLE, UNTARGETABLE and UNAFFECTED by cards effects! This means that your opponent will mostly be helpless as you amass resources and combo up to your win conditions Chaos Ancient Gear Giant and Ultimate Ancient Gear Golem! 
 
Ancient Gear Dark Golem, Ancient Gear Statue, Ancient Gear Advance, Ancient Gear Commander, Ancient Gear Tanker and Ancient Gear Duel all make it much easier to generate an entire army of Ancient Gear juggernauts to obliterate all your opponent's board and lifepoints! There is now a heavy emphasis on Dr. Crowler's ace monster, Ancient Gear Golem, and now we're actually incentivized to summon it a lot and make fusion boss monsters like Ultimate Ancient Gear Golem and Megaton Golem! 
 
Let's blind second and teach these lame SLIFER RED duelists in Duelist Cup what the true meaning of having a PhD in dueling, just like our beloved Dr. Vellian Crowler! Time to blind second and MECHANIZED MELEE!!!

deck_excerpt: Witches smoke & mirrors , Witchcrafter , Albaz , Diabellstar , Branded , Spellcaster , Dragon , TCG , NEW Witchcrafter , 2025 Deck
deck_description:
This deck is a work in progress but I think its a solid starting point for the power level of what witchcrafters can do.I built the deck with going 2ed in mind but it can also go first and this is going to depend on what deck you're going up against. You want to go 2ed for the 6th card for bigger plays unless your match up is a deck you can't let set up a board then go first.

When going 2ed you can do some of the following...

Ultimate Slayer - To send monsters on there board back to there deck that may give you issues (its not once perturn and they can't use monster cards to respond so its not a bad way to start breaking the board. Also when going 1st its not a bad idea to use Spellbound in place of this card or using Super Polymerization going 1st or 2ed although the Super Polymerization is not always the best to try and go into Witchcrafter Vice-Madame unless you know there going to have a spellcaster or same match up but its a spell just toss it for cost at worst)

Diabellstar the Black Witch - If you did not draw into Ultimate Slayer you can special summon Diabellstar the Black Witch and set to the board from deck Sinful Spoils of Subversion - Snake-Eye to shut off one of there monsters or get rid of a monster you can't beat over. If the board does not look that bad just for for Sinful Spoils of Doom - Rciela or when going first its a good card to set so you can pop cards with low ATK before they go into bigger monsters or atleast take less damage from there bigger ATK monsters. (You often search Diabellstar the Black Witch with WANTED: Seeker of Sinful Spoils to add to hand)

Incredible Ecclesia, the Virtuous - When you go 2ed more times then not will be able to special summon this card for free then use her effect to bring out The Iris Swordsoul and you can also go into Fallen of Albaz as well this way from deck or hand.

The Iris Swordsoul - If you happen to draw into this card and don't have Incredible Ecclesia, the Virtuous in hand to just summon it you can wait for your opponent to negate any monster effect and just summon her to the board or you can also go into Witchcrafter Madame Verre and negate there effect monsters and chain to summon as well.

Witchcrafter Unveiling - This card is super good with any of the witchcrafter monsters as using this card will force out a negate or "your opponent cannot activate cards or effects in response to the activation of your Spellcaster monster effects for the rest of this turn." (Not just Witchcrafters yes all spellcasters)

 

 

 

Reasoning - Well its Reasoning and this deck using lots of levels so even when your opponent knows your deck there is still a good chance they guess wrong so its a free summon and body that really helps this deck and even if it fails maybe you get lucky enough to have a few extra tools in the GY to help you out. ( This card its just too good and at worst its still a spell to use for cost for your other cards that need spells in this deck also if you just want to be super funny go into your Diabell, Queen of the White Forest using a Tuner Synchro Monster and add Reasoning to your hand and use it again because its not once perturn)

Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous - If you just so happen to get Fallen of Albaz on the board or in your GY then you can also summon this girl for free and this is the main way you're going to want to go into Witchcrafter Vice-Madame and if it all possible well you can use her as a spellcaster you really want to keep her on the board for her Synchro plays because after you summon Witchcrafter Vice-Madame you do any action to triger Witchcrafter Vice-Madame and use her special summon effect to summing a level 2 , 3 or 4 or what ever you need for the synchros in the profile or ones you added.You can also do this to go into XYZ plays as well or Links.

Witchcrafter Confusion Confession - is nice when in hand with Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous you just summon the Cartesia and go for her Quick effect and when your opponent negates it you just follow up with Witchcrafter Confusion Confession and when its in your deck this is what you do when you don't have Cartesia... You normal summing Genni or Schmietta and use there effect to summon a Genni or Schmietta.. Then you will link ontop of the one thats left on the board with your link one in this case I use Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden to do this sending the card to the GY. What has happen at this point is you put both Genni and Schmietta in the GY. You use Schmietta effect to send from deck to GY Witchcrafter Confusion Confession and use Genni to copy the effect of Witchcrafter Confusion Confession by banishing both cards from the GY to use Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden and what ever other witchcrafter you have in your hand or field to then go into Witchcrafter Vice-Madame. (This tends to not end up in big boards but, it gets your boss monster on the board never the less... you also may be able to use this as a follow up if you got negated before as now your opponent will have to have GY hate to stop this)

Monster Reborn - Its to act as the 3rd copy of Witchcrafter Holiday and to bring back things that Witchcrafter Holiday can't it also helps with not drawing into 2 or 3 copies of Witchcrafter Holiday because that card is once per turn so it can be used with Holiday to bring back 2 cards if drawn together. Monster Reborn is also not once perturn so if you get it back with effect of Diabell, Queen of the White Forest you can use it again. Likewise you can use Witchcrafter Holiday effect in the GY with Genni with her effect so in a low chance you could end up with 4 GY special summons. 

Witchcrafter Vice-Madame - She is the main boss you often want on the board and each turn you can use all 3 of her effects so you want to set up ways and play in ways to tringer her so you can chain with her. Any spell card or spellcaster effect will triger her and you can pick any of the 3 effects to use. She as a non target pop that is super good... I found using the pop on my own Diabellstar the Black Witch was super useful on my opponents turn as you pop her with Vice effect then she goes to the GY and as soon as she gets there the Black Witch is going to chain 1 asking if you want to summon back to the board from there you Chain Vice as chain link 2 and use one of her other effects then when Black Witch is back on the board she starts another Chain 1 asking you if you want to set a target from deck and you Chain Vice to that as well as Chain link 2 using another effect. So you end up with a level 6 or lower witchcrafter on the board and a add back to hand with Black Witch still on the board by popping Black Witch and from there you can use the effects of your level 6 or lower witchcrafter to go into bigger cards.You can also pop card like Vahram, the Magistus Divinity Dragon to say goodbye to your opponents board if they let you do this.

Witchcrafter Golem Aruru - Is super great and easy to add to hand. She protects all spellcasters not just witchcrafters from card effects or attack but, only when there being targeted so do keep this in mind. Its a bounce back to hand though and she can also add a witchcrafter spell from your GY back to your hand giving your other witchcrafters the cost they need to use there effects as well as she sits on the board till your opponent standby phase meaning when she returns to hand she also is a triger for Witchcrafter Vice-Madame and from there you can summon or use one of her other effects so its really good in this way and Aruru protects herself in this way going back to your hand as well as she is a handtrap so she is where she needs to be.

Fortune Lady Every - Not a must have card but she keeps getting stonger and stonger in ATK power and is a force to mess with well with Witchcrafter Haine, Witchcrafter Madame Verre and Witchcrafter Golem Aruru and because of her standby phase effect she also trigers Witchcrafter Vice-Madame giving you two non target effects Vice pops and Lady Every banishs one of there monsters.

Lyna the Light Charmer, Lustrous - You could change her out to any of her counter parts for main matchups but, I put her in her because well light cards are common but, also because she has some of the most value to the deck being she can add "add 1 LIGHT monster with 1500 or less DEF from your Deck to your hand." This means you can add cards like Witchcrafter Golem Aruru, Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous and Incredible Ecclesia, the Virtuous.

Bystial Magnamhut , Awakening of the Possessed - Rasenryu and Ranryu - I'm still testing this but going 1st I think its a better 3 of then the Incredible Ecclesia, the Virtuous and The Iris Swordsoul.

There is a lot this deck can do but its Witchcrafters at the end of the day and with decks now playing 15+ handtraps its going to be hard. The deck could be pushed a little more with some of the new White Forest main deck cards and other cards like Guiding Quem, the Virtuous but at this time cards like this are too much in cost for me to want to get into them.

Have fun even if you just use this deck as a idea to build from. I know witchcrafters are not a great deck vs anything that even comes close to meta but I do think witchcrafters are stonger then people often see this deck so iv been making it a goal to push this deck as far as I can useing mostly budget cards and keeping the heart of the deck still Witchcrafters. I think I mostly achieved this with what I have here and im going to keep working on it. I hope to see a level 6 for this deck at some point as we don't have one depsite Vice saying level 6 or under so there is also hope for support for this deck among loads of room in the extra deck.
Budget Generaider. Still working on a side deck.

deck_excerpt: Why violence? Decorate a tree instead.
deck_description:
In the most unlikely of places, a Domain Format Battlefield, set up the tree of peace the spirit of Christmas! This is a deck that goes "shopping" through our deck using the deckmaster Shining Angel to collect the pieces we need to set up and decorate a tree for Christmas. We will collect the tree, the presents, the ornaments, and of course the topper! But our opponents can help! By summoning our Deckmaster back on our opponent's turn (using cards like Ultimeat Offering and Ultimate Offering), we can ask them to channel Christmas Spirit and destroy our Shining Angel by battle to accelerate our shopping! Lets all Decorate a Christmas Tree Together!

Here is the collection of pieces present in the deck, we can mix and match for different trees.

Trees: Seed-Spitting Saplings, The World Tree, Spiritual Forest, Benghalancer the Resurgent, Crystal Tree, Ragnaraika Wisteria of Woe(Silhouhatte Rabbit), Naturia Sacred Tree     

Decorations: Shining Piecephilia, Ceremonial Bell, Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres, Sinister Seeds(Sinister Seed Token) , Photon Sanctuary(Photon Token) 

Presents: Toy Box(Toy Soldier), Pinpoint Dash, Chicken Game, Gift Exchange, Gift Card, The Gift of Greed, Black Garden, Extra Net, Box of Friends, Double-Edged Sword(Ohime the Manifested Mikanko)        

Topper: Hip Hoshiningen, Hoshiningen, Barrier Statue of the Heavens, Angel Statue - Azurune(Silhouhatte Rabbit), Kuebiko(Silhouhatte Rabbit), Linkerbell, Shining Angel   

Light the Tree: DNA Transplant, RGB Rainbowlution  

We also ask our opponents to channel the feeling of forgiveness and benovolance through cards that give them a choice:

Death Forgivness: Monster Reborn Reborn, Intimidating Ore - Summonite, Painful Return   

Genorosity: Creature Swap, Heroic Gift, Gift Exchange, Yaminabe Party , One or Eight 

Lastly, we have fun mini-games we start to get the feeling of Chrismas gathering going!

Coin Flip Guesser!: Head Judging 

What's the card? Guess!: Ordeal of a Traveler , Tri-and-Guess 

Who can target the GY the fastest?: Out of the Blue 

Spells Hot Potato!: Tower of Babel 

LP Lowering Limbo: Chicken Game 

Roll Higher!: Dice Jar 

Heres some Chrismas Trees we can make: 

 

Join the Domain Format Discord: https://discord.gg/FGUmaXXd

deck_name: Ruin & Demise - Impcantation cheap deck for MasterDuel (+6SR & +2UR)
deck_description:
This is a very cheap deck which can be used for every ritual archetype. The basic idea was to summon the "Demise, King of Armageddon" ritual monster to break the field and then with the help of "Ruin, Supreme Queen of Oblivion" monster (which can attack 2 times in a row if summoned correctly) to attack with these 2 cards for game.

But these restrictions makes this strategy a bit of impossible. So my next approach was to bring the "Demise, King of Armageddon" monster and then with "Crealtar, the Impcantation Originator" monster + 2 other Impcantation monsters to hit for 9400 LP. 

This might not be that easy to execute as a first turn kill cause of handtraps and other disruptions that can slow the process. This deck contains some small draw engines as Spellbooks and DarkMagicians which can help a lot with cycling through materials and pieces of the combo.

Impcantation Ratios: Most of the times Ritual monsters are way more accessible, cause we use more of them. The main reason for that is that Impcantation ritual spell can be retrieved from grave. So it's smarter to use more of level 3 and level 6 Impcantation monsters to activate them from hand. The level 10 Boss monster can even suffle them back to deck if needed, to never run out of resources.

Cards like "Swords of concealing light" and "Gravity bind" can help with slowing down your opponent, while they can be pretty good targets for "Magicians' Souls" (to send them to grave and draw some cards). "Gravity Bind" might be annoying for you aswell but it can be destroyed in your turn by using the effect of "Demise, King of Armageddon" to remove it from the field. Some other good targets to discard with "Magicians' Souls" are "Rise to full Height", "Lost Wind" and "Galaxy Cyclone".

You can always use even better ritual monsters to end your opponent as Chaos Max Dragon which has some sort of build-in protection. That's why you should look at the side deck for more options.

I am a bit lazy with the extra deck cause Impcantation non-ritual monsters prevent you from special summoning from the extra deck. But that's not true when you summon "Crealtar, the Impcantation Originator" which negates the effects of all impcantation non-ritual monsters. So you can always extend your combos even further. I just don't feel like I have to do it.

-----IMPORTANT NOTE-----

This is an approach I've not tested that much and it's more expensive than this one: https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/armageddon-impcantation-cheap-deck-for-masterduel-551502
