deck_excerpt: Did you know that sanctuary in the sky is actually Santa's workshop?  Thats where they make all the Fluffal toys!
deck_description: One day while Santa was away, something strange happened. While all of santa's helper elves QA cupids were play testing the days toys, they noticed some of the factory machines we're acting strangely. The Fluffals were filled with sharp objects and the Snowmen were eating people! They began investigating and found out that the workshop was being overrun with naughty list energy. Without Santa around, the balance of nice and naughty energy was in flux. Just as they were about to take action, the machines started whirring up once again and, to everyones surprise, started making naughty versions of the staff! A war began between between the two factions unlike anything seen before. Just when things looked most dire, Chaos Goddess Mrs.Clause came to the rescue! With her swift action and solemn judgment, she was able to restore balance and save Christmas! The nice and naughty angels were able to put aside their differences and enjoy a day of peace and prosperity!

deck_description: Extra deck is pretty barebones, but should get the job done, if you have other cards youd like to include, there's room. deck_name: Degenerate FTK Player's Guide to Gimmick Puppet (December 2024) (Masterduel)
deck_excerpt: Masterduel's STRONGEST and most CONSISTENT FTK deck - Gimmick Puppet!
deck_description:
With the support from Masterduel's Selection Pack "Chaotic Showtime," Quattro's Gimmick Puppets transformed from an obscure, weak anime deck into a nearly unstoppable first turn kill powerhouse! Mansion of the Dreadful Dolls renders your Gimmick Puppet combo UNAFFECTED by monster based handtraps as well as monster interruption! With this absolutely cracked field spell, going first and second suddenly became much easier for the strategy, especially since Gimmick Puppets burn for the entirety of your opponent's lifepoints going first, and going second, opponent's boards are naturally cleared as you fly through the combos.
 
Rouge Doll is another incredible card, acting as this deck's "Exosister Martha," summoning herself and another Gimmick Puppet from deck for further XYZ plays! Not only that, she recurs herself the GY as soon as she hits hit (for ex. Getting detached for foolish'd) granting this strategy a robust grind game. Little Soldier'ss gives the deck it's best normal summon and 1-card combo in the form of a foolish burial. Cattle Scream gives the deck a free body to XYZ summon with and more ways to summon monsters on your opponent's side of the field to enable the burn FTK. 
 
I thought the burn FTK was just like it's namesake - a gimmick. But in reality, I was pleasantly surprised during testing that Quattro's macabre puppets can really win games with their "fan service!" Gimmick Puppet is like the burn version of "Tenpai Dragon." They know the FTK is coming, they try as much as possible to stop it, but it still succeeds! As Quattro would often say... "NOW THAT'S TRUE FANSERVICE!"
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
While Gimmick Puppet is played "pure," it uses a Horus package to support the strategy. Finally, the usual mandatory Masterduel staples are used. 
 
The GIMMICK PUPPET cards constitute the main strategy, forming the majority of the deck. Due to the consistency boosts from the new support, the deck core is relatively small. Rouge Doll, Little Soldiers, Mansion of the Dreadful Dolls and Condolence Puppet are all used at 3 since they are starters. Two each of Terror Baby, Cattle Scream and Argent Chaos Force are used since they are garnets and mostly need to be searched from deck as part of the combo. Finally, Service Puppet Play is the search target for Fanatix Machinix, enabling the deck to interrupt the opponent if they manage to survive the burn FTK. 
 
A HORUS engine is used to enable rank 8 plays and to give Set Rotation another target to go into. King's Sarcophagus is also a great discard outlet for cards you want to get out of your hand, like if you happen to draw your garnets of Bisque Doll and Terror Baby who have beneficial effects in the GY. 
 
The rest of the deck is composed of STAPLES to ensure the FTK combo goes through successfully. Double Called By the Grave, x3 Ash Blossom, x2 Maxx "C," x1 Crossout and it's targets x1 Veiler, Imperm, Nibiru and Droll.  
 
While this deck needs to be consistent, so it is 40 cards sharp to enable to FTK to go though with as much protection as possible. 
 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
Gimmick Puppets are infamous for being an extremely effective FTK burn strategy. Gimmick Puppet is almost like the burn version of "Tenpai Dragon." The fieldspell searches a starter, and it renders Gimmick Puppet monsters nigh untouchable as you weave through the combo. 
 
Here are several burn FTK combos for Gimmick Puppet: 
 
Mansion of the Dreadful Dolls = Burn for 9300 + Service Puppet Play (Steal opponent's monsters)
  1. Activate Mansion of the Underworld Dolls. Add from hand Little Soldiers.  
  2. Normal Little Soldier, send to GY Rouge Doll. 
  3. Activate Rouge Doll's GY effect to add it from the GY to hand. 
  4. Activate Rouge Doll's hand effect to summon herself hand, reveal any rank 8 from Extra Deck and summon Cattle Scream from deck. 
  5. XYZ summon Fantasix Makina using Little Soldiers and Cattle Scream. 
  6. Activate Fantasix Makina's effect to detach Cattle Scream and add from deck Rank-Up Magic Argent Chaos Force. 
  7. Activate Argent Chaos Force targeting Fantasix Makina to rank it up into Dark Strings. 
  8. Summon Cattle Scream from the GY by detaching a material from Dark Strings. 
  9. XYZ summon Puppet of Strings using Cattle Scream and Rouge Doll. 
  10. Activate Argent Chaos Force's trigger effect in the GY to add itself back to hand. 
  11. Activate Puppet of Strings effect to place a String Counter on Dark Strings. 
  12. Activate Argent Chaos Force targeting Puppet of Strings to rank it up into another Dark Strings. 
  13. Activate Dark String's trigger effect in CL1 to destroy as many monsters with String Counters as possible, draw 1 card, and burn your opponent for 3300 (the ATK of the destroyed Dark Strings). In CL2, activate Fantasix Makina's effect to summon itself from the GY. 
  14. Activate Argent Chaos Force's trigger effect in the GY to add itself back to hand. 
  15. Activate Mansion's effect to detach 1 material from your Dark Strings on the field to summon the Dark Strings in the GY to your opponent's field. 
  16. Activate Argent Chaos Force targeting Fantasix Makina to rank up into the Chaos version of the card: CXYZ Gimmick Puppet Fanatix Makinix. 
  17. Activate Fanatix Makinix's effect to add a Gimmick Puppet trap from your deck (typically Service Puppet Play). If your opponent manages to live to the next turn, you still have an interruption!
  18. Activate Fanatix's effect detaching 1 card to summon to your opponent's side of the field Puppet of Strings. 
  19. Link summon Chimera Doll using Fanatix + Dark Strings. 
  20. Activate Chimera Doll's effect to add from deck Terror Baby. 
  21. Normal summon Terror Baby to summon from GY Cattle Scream. 
  22. Banish Little Soldiers from GY targeting Terror Baby to make it a level 8. 
  23. XYZ summon Giant Grinder using Terror Baby + Cattle Scream. 
  24. Detach from Giant Grinder twice targeting both Dark Strings and Puppet of Strings on your opponent's side of the field to burn for 3300 and 3000. You burn your opponent for a grand total of 9300!
Mansion of the Dreadful Dolls = Burn for 8100 + Draw 3 cards + Service Puppet Play (Steal opponent's monsters)
 
  1. Repeat steps 1-6 from the first combo. 
  2. Activate Argent Chaos Force targeting Fantasix Makina to rank it up into Fanatix Makinix. 
  3. Activate Fanatix Makinix's effect to add a Gimmick Puppet trap from your deck (typically Service Puppet Play). If your opponent manages to live to the next turn, you still have an interruption!
  4. Summon Cattle Scream from the GY by detaching a material from Fanatix Makinix. 
  5. XYZ summon Puppet of Strings using Rouge Doll and Cattle Scream. 
  6. Activate Argent Chaos Force's trigger effect in the GY to add itself back to hand. 
  7. Activate Puppet of Strings effect to place a String Counter on Fanatix Makinix. 
  8. Activate Fanatix's effect detaching 1 card to summon to your opponent's side of the field Cattle Scream. 
  9. Activate Argent Chaos Force targeting Puppet of Strings to rank it up into Dark Strings. 
  10. Activate Dark String's trigger effect in CL1 to destroy as many monsters with String Counters as possible, draw 1 card, and burn your opponent for 3100 (the ATK of the destroyed Dark Strings). In CL2, activate Fantasix Makina's effect to summon itself from the GY.
  11. Activate Argent Chaos Force's trigger effect in the GY to add itself back to hand. 
  12. Detach a material from Dark Strings to put a String counter on Cattle Scream on your opponent's field. 
  13. Activate Argent Chaos Force targeting Fantasix Makina to rank it up into Dark Strings. 
  14. Activate Dark String's trigger effect again to destroy as many monsters with String Counters as possible, draw another 1 card, and burn your opponent for 2000 (the ATK of the destroyed Cattle Scream).
  15. Activate Mansion's effect to detach 1 material from your Dark Strings on the field to summon the Puppet of Strings in the GY to your opponent's field. 
  16. Detach a material from Dark Strings to put a String counter on Puppet of Strings on your opponent's field. 
  17. Link summon Chimera Doll using Dark Strings + Dark Strings. 
  18. Activate Chimera Doll's effect to add from deck Terror Baby.
  19. Normal summon Terror Baby to summon from GY Dark Strings.
  20. Activate Dark String's trigger effect for the third time to destroy as many monsters with String Counters as possible, draw another 1 card, and burn your opponent for 3000 (the ATK of the destroyed Puppet of Strings). You burn your opponent for a grand total of 8100 AND draw 3 cards in the process!
 
Little Soldiers + Any Level 8 Gimmick Puppet = 
 
  1. Repeat steps 1-6 from the first combo.
  2. Activate Argent Chaos Force targeting Fantasix Makina to rank it up into Fanatix Makinix.
  3. Activate Fanatix Makinix's effect to add a Gimmick Puppet trap from your deck (typically Service Puppet Play). If your opponent manages to live to the next turn, you still have an interruption!
  4. Summon Cattle Scream from the GY by detaching a material from Fanatix Makinix.
  5. XYZ summon Puppet of Strings using Rouge Doll and Cattle Scream.
  6. Activate Argent Chaos Force's trigger effect in the GY to add itself back to hand.
  7. Activate Puppet of Strings effect to place a String Counter on Fanatix Makinix.
  8. Activate Fanatix's effect detaching 1 card to summon to your opponent's side of the field Cattle Scream.
  9. Activate Argent Chaos Force targeting Puppet of Strings to rank it up into Dark Strings.
  10. Activate Dark String's trigger effect in CL1 to destroy as many monsters with String Counters as possible, draw 1 card, and burn your opponent for 3100 (the ATK of the destroyed Dark Strings). In CL2, activate Fantasix Makina's effect to summon itself from the GY.
  11. Activate Argent Chaos Force's trigger effect in the GY to add itself back to hand.
  12. Detach a material from Dark Strings to put a String counter on Cattle Scream on your opponent's field.
  13. Activate Argent Chaos Force targeting Fantasix Makina to rank it up into Dark Strings.
  14. Activate Dark String's trigger effect again to destroy as many monsters with String Counters as possible, draw another 1 card, and burn your opponent for 2000 (the ATK of the destroyed Cattle Scream).
 
You can also more or less replicate either combo without Mansion of the Dreadful Dolls by having Little Soldiers + any level 8 Gimmick Puppet. The only difference is that your Gimmick Puppet Monsters on the field will be affected by your opponent's non-XYZ monster effects, especially handtraps. If you also lack a level 8 body, Horus monsters are excellent extenders. 
 
Unlike other FTK decks, Gimmick Puppets actually do well at breaking boards, especially while Mansion is active. Going second, Gimmick Puppets naturally break boards as they combo through Gigantes Doll, Giant Grinder, Puppet of Strings and Dark Strings. All the while, Mansion of Dreadful Doll renders your monsters nearly invincible vs. your opponent's monster-based interruption (except XYZ monsters like Zeus and TY-Phon). Horus monsters paired with Gold Sarcophagus remove monsters through the battle phase effectively as well. 

 
GENERAL TIPS
  • The Horus monsters are excellent extenders if you lack a level 8 body to XYZ summon with. The Horus cards also excel at removal of hard to out monsters in the Battle Phase. 
  • Despite your Gimmick Puppet monsters not affected on the field while Mansion is active, you're still vulnerable to handtraps like Maxx C, Droll, Shifter, Imperm and Bystials. Remember, this deck has many extenders (Horus, Biqsue Doll, Chimera Doll, Terror Baby) so you can still potentially play through those specific handtraps!
  • If your FTK have been interrupted into a standstill and you lack resources to complete the shift, the trap card Service Puppet Play is your next play. Summon as many XYZ monsters as possible so you can quick effect steal your opponent's monsters. 
  • This strategy also naturally excels at breaking apart established boards. Gimmick Puppet's innate ability to summon big beatsticks, clear boards en-masse, unaffected combolines due to Mansion, and the Horus engine's brute force pressures most boards to fall apart. After you simplify your opponent's gamestate, you can start the FTK! 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
Recently, Konami keeps pretty insane field spells for archetypes they want to see meta competitive play. Almost like how Invoked has "Magical Meltdown," the fieldspell renders your archetypal cards unaffected! First Tenpai, then Yubel, and now out of nowhere... Gimmick Puppet?! 
 
Gimmick Puppet certainly has made it's own unique niche as the competitive "burn deck!" Despite how degenerate and un-interactive it is, it's kind of exciting that in a tier 0 format dominated by ridiculously expensive 1-card combo engines that burn FTK can make its mark. 
 
Being a burn FTK is kind of thematically relevant too, since your opponent doesn't get to play - all they do is watch in awe as you control the strings of the horrific puppet show! In the words of Quattro... "NOW THAT'S TRUE FANSERVICE!"
 
GLHF Duelists!

deck_description:
Sorry about the re-edits and reuploads. For some reason, Edopro has Lady's Dragonmaid's card ID as Rescue-ACE Air Lifter and Dragonmaid Stern's card ID as Rescue-ACE Impulse. Importing the YDK from Edopro to this site had Impulse show up in the Main Deck instead of Stern and had Air Lifter in the Extra Deck instead of Lady's Dragonmaid which is funny but not what I wanted lol. You might see that being the case for some other people's Dragonmaid Decks with the QCTB support FYI.

Dragonmaid has gotten some interesting pieces of support out of the OCG’s Quarter Century Trinity Box, and for what it is, it is really quite special. But most importantly, they have a new Level 9 monster. Dragonmaid Stern is a Level 9 DARK Dragon monster which can discard itself to Special Summon a Dragonmaid monster from your GY or banishment other than itself, while it is on the field Dragon Fusions you control cannot be destroyed by your opponent’s card effects, and at the end of the Battle Phase, you can return it to the hand to Special Summon a Level 4 or lower Dragonmaid from your hand. Being able to Special Summon a Dragonmaid from GY or banishment is excellent for recursion or extension, but put into our goal of putting a Level 9 monster on the field to target with World Legacy Monstrosity, Stern is not the best candidate for that. Looking at the in-archetype effects that Special Summon a Dragonmaid monster, there is no real consistently good way to put Stern onto the field, and it is not like she actually does much on the field either way. So, we are going to still focus on Special Summoning Dragonmaid’s other Level 9, House Dragonmaid. She is a Level 9 LIGHT Dragon Fusion Monster that requires a Dragonmaid and a Dragon as material. As a soft once per turn during the Standby Phase, you can target another Dragonmaid monster you control to Special Summon a Dragonmaid from your hand or GY whose Level is 1 higher or 1 lower, and when another Dragon monster(s) you control returns to your hand, you can target and pop a monster your opponent controls. We are still going to be using Stern in our combo to get to House, but we are going to be making use of Dragonmaid’s second new piece of support: Lady’s Dragonmaid. Lady’s is a Fusion Monster that requires 2 Dragonmaids with the same Attribute but with different Levels, and she must first be Special Summoned from the Extra Deck by banishing 1 material monster from your field and 1 material monster from your GY. She is important here because on Special Summon, she can Special Summon a Level 4 or lower Dragonmaid from your Deck which is just an incredible effect to have on a very easily accessible monster. We are going to be aiming towards Special Summoning Lady’s Dragonmaid who will then Special Summon Parlor Dragonmaid from Deck who then dumps Dragonmaid Changeover from Deck, returning both it and Parlor to hand, giving us the ability to Fusion Summon House Dragonmaid. 

Full combo is Chamber Dragonmaid + World Legacy Monstrosity. It isn’t that consistently openable and there are other ways to actually achieve full combo (except they also require Monstrosity). But unless you are playing Dragon Rulers or some other generic Dragon searchers (can’t think of any others off the top of my head), you aren’t going to be opening these exact 2 cards that often. But WAIT A MINUTE: “Why aren’t you playing Kitchen Dragonmaid and Dragonmaid Tinkhec?” Well that’s because we are trying to make House Dragonmaid while keeping Lady’s Dragonmaid on field to Fusion Summon Dragonmaid Sheou during the next Standby Phase. If we did play Kitchen and Tinkhec, we wouldn’t be able to access Sheou on our opponent’s turn while also getting out House on our turn. Plus, we would have to play Tinkhec which does literally nothing. I’m not playing a card that is basically Elemental HERO Honest Neos for Dragonmaids in my Deck. Besides, you are still going to play Dragonmaid Hospitality if you do use Kitchen over Chamber because it gives you access to Lady’s Dragonmaid if you happen to draw it and a dragon form Dragonmaid. The Deck has a good endboard, but the starting hand is hard to achieve (and I am certainly not playing Kitchen Dragonmaid for the previous reasons and because I think that it is one of the worst searchers ever made). Normal Chamber and activate her effect to search for Dragonmaid Hospitality. Link Chamber into Striker Dragon. Activate Hospitality to bring back Chamber and dump Dragonmaid Stern from Deck to GY. Banish Chamber and Stern to Special Summon Lady’s Dragonmaid from Extra Deck. Lady’s Dragonmaid activates to Special Summon Parlor Dragonmaid from Deck who then activates to send Dragonmaid Changeover from Deck to GY. Changeover bounces Parlor to hand and adds it to hand. Activate Changeover to Fusion Summon House Dragonmaid using Parlor in hand and Striker Dragon on field. Activate Monstrosity targeting House Dragonmaid for Prediction Princess Bibliomuse and Deus-X Krawler from Deck. From there, it is the same old Prediction Princess combo except, we are also ending with Lady’s Dragonmaid on field. During your opponent’s Standby Phase, after you Special Summon Bibliomuse from Deck face-down with Underworld Ritual of Prediction’s GY effect, flip Tarotreith face-up with Tarotrei, and use Tarotreith to flip Bibliomuse and Deus-X face-up, Lady’s Dragonmaid can Fusion Summon Dragonmaid Sheou from Extra Deck by shuffling itself and a banished Dragonmaid into the Deck. Now, you have Sheou as an omni-negate who replaces herself with a House Dragonmaid from Extra Deck for a Level 9 for next turn. 

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's effect in the End Phase. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down after being Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute. 1 Pot of the Forbidden which has a Flip Effect that lets you choose between Drawing 2 cards, returning all Spell/Traps on the field to the hand, destroying all monsters your opponent controls, or looking at your opponent's hand and shuffling a card from it back into the Deck. 2 Dragonmaid Stern. 3 Chamber Dragonmaid. On Normal or Special Summon, she can add a Dragonmaid Spell/Trap from Deck to hand and at the start of the Battle Phase, she can return herself from field to hand to Special Summon a Level 7 or higher Dragonmaid from hand or GY. Chamber is a really important card in this Deck and pretty much any Dragonmaid Deck. The Dragonmaid Spell/Traps (for the most part) achieve much more than most of their Main Deck monsters, so just being able to search for one is really good. And in this Deck, we are using Chamber to search for specifically Dragonmaid Hospitality to get the required monsters for the Special Summon of Lady’s Dragonmaid on field and in GY. 1 Dragonmaid Lorpar which cannot be destroyed by card effects while you control a Fusion Monster and you can discard her and target a face-up monster on field to prevent both players from activating that monster’s effects for the turn. And at the end of the Battle Phase, you can return her to hand to Special Summon a Level 3 Dragonmaid from hand. Lorpar is just here as a send off of Hospitality if we have Parlor Dragonmaid in hand or GY or if we draw her and Hospitality, we can use her to send Parlor from Deck to GY with Hospitality instead. Basically, if we draw either Lorpar or Parlor with Hospitality but we do not have access to Chamber, we can still gain access to Lady’s Dragonmaid. Speaking of, we are playing 2 Parlor Dragonmaid. On Summon, she sends a Dragonmaid card from Deck to GY and at the start of the Battle Phase, you can return her to hand to Special Summon a Level 8 Dragonmaid from hand or GY. Again, we are using Parlor to send Dragonmaid Changeover who will then bounce Parlor back to hand to add it from GY to hand for you to be able to activate Changeover and Fusion Summon. We are only playing 2 because we would have to specifically draw Parlor and Hospitality in order to gain access to Lady’s Dragonmaid. I would much rather accidentally draw either of the two rather than hope that I draw both. Finally, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring. 

For Spell/Traps: 1 Instant Fusion for Master of Ham. 3 Pre-Preparation of Rites which searches a Ritual Spell from Deck and a Ritual Monster from Deck or GY whose name is mentioned on that card. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 2 Prediction Ritual which can only Ritual Summon Prediction Princess Tarotrei, and you can banish it from GY except the turn it was sent there to search for a Prediction Princess monster. 1 Pot of Prosperity. 2 Dragonmaid Hospitality which Special Summons a Dragonmaid from your hand or GY in Defense Position and then you can send a Dragonmaid monster with the same Attribute but a different Level from your Deck to the GY. The more that I read this card, the better that it gets. For one, it Special Summons a Dragonmaid from hand or GY which can either act as recursion or extension and then it gives you the option of basically sending the maid form or dragon form of the Dragonmaid monster you Summoned from Deck to GY. For Dragonmaid straight out of Mystic Fighters, this gave you access to the dragon forms as soon as you got into the Battle Phase as the maids can Special Summon the dragon forms from hand OR GY. But with the support coming out of QCTB, this card in conjunction with a Dragonmaid in hand or GY sets you up completely to Special Summon Lady’s Dragonmaid from Extra Deck. 1 Dragonmaid Changeover which Fusion Summons a Dragon Fusion Monster from your Extra Deck using monsters from your hand or field as Fusion Material and while it is in your GY, you can target a Dragonmaid you control to add this card back to hand and bounce that monster back to hand as well. 1 Foolish Burial. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from your hand or target a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different type and Attribute, but with different names. And finally, 3 Infinite Impermanence. 

Extra Deck: 1 Dragonmaid Sheou which is a Fusion Monster that requires a Dragonmaid monster and a Level 5 or higher Dragon monster as Fusion Material. During each Standby Phase, you can Special Summon a Level 9 or lower Dragonmaid from hand or GY and when your opponent activates a card or effect, you can Quick Effect negate the activation and destroy that card and then you return Sheou to the Extra Deck and Special Summon a House Dragonmaid from Extra Deck. 2 House Dragonmaid. 1 Lady’s Dragonmaid which is a Fusion that requires 2 Dragonmaid monsters with the same Attribute but different Levels. There are many aspects of this monster that you have to pay attention to in order to not accidentally make an illegal play. For starters, Lady’s Dragonmaid must first be Special Summoned from the Extra Deck by banishing 1 each of its materials from field and GY. This means that you need to banish 1 Dragonmaid monster you control and 1 Dragonmaid monster from your GY with the same Attribute but different Levels to Special Summon her from Extra. You can’t banish 2 Dragonmaids you control or 2 Dragonmaids from your GY. It has to be 1 Dragonmaid monster from both locations. If she is Special Summoned, you can Special Summon a Level 4 or lower Dragonmaid monster from your Deck. And during the Standby Phase, you can Fusion Summon a Dragon Fusion Monster from your Extra Deck by shuffling its materials from your field and/or banishment into the Deck. Field and/or banishment, NOT GY. Don’t make that mistake. 1 Master of Ham which can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which adds a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from your Deck to your hand if it is sent to the GY. 1 Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 S:P Little Knight. 1 Gravity Controller. And 1 Striker Dragon which is a LINK-1 that requires a Level 4 or lower Dragon monster which we are using to Link off Chamber Dragonmaid. Why don’t we play Salamangreat Almiraj? Well, Striker Dragon is a Dragon monster which is one of the Fusion Material requirements for House Dragonmaid while Almiraj isn’t. 

Side Deck: 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 1 Bystial Magnamhut, 1 Bystial Druiswurm, 3 Triple Tactics Thrust, 2 Triple Tactics Talent, 1 Change of Heart, 1 Called by the Grave, 1 Harpie’s Feather Duster, and 3 Dimensional Barrier. Keep in mind that Magnamhut’s search of a Dragon from Deck or GY during the End Phase can search for a copy of Dragonmaid Stern which brings back a Dragonmaid from GY or banishment, so we can bring back say a House Dragonmaid from GY for a Level 9 body for a Rank 9 play into Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows.
Use Ryu Okami bring opponent extra deck to the GY

Make Fusion Monsters. Use Versago The Destroyer To Make Fusion Monsters Without Needing The Correct Material. Instant Fusion Can Only Be Used To Summon Alligator's Sword Dragon As It Is The Only Level 5 Fusion Monster In The Deck.

deck_excerpt: I could eat a Heavy Borgor

deck_description:
*any of these cards are full combo: ankh, milennium shield, sengenin, heart of the blue eyes

combo 1 (for this combo we will use millennium shield and sengenin, lets also pretend we didnt start with ankh in our starting hand)

1) summon out shield in the s/t zone, pay 2000 LP to summon to field to search ankh from deck to hand

2) place senginjin in s/t zone, reveal the ankh and summon senginin to field

3) senginin effect to add either blue eyes or golem to hand (for the sake of this combo lets say we choose golem to add to hand)

4) place golem in the s/t zone, reveal the ankh to summon golem to field

5) golem effect to search wedju temple from deck to hand, activate temple to place up to 2 milennium monsters in s/t

6) activate ankh, reveal 5 pieces of exodia to fusion into exodia incarnate, ankh shuffles back into deck

7) summon village of spellcasters (if you drew it in starting hand)

8) end turn, exodia effect to set exxod fires of rage face down

9) on opponent's end phase set obliterate blaze face down

 

combo 2 ( for this next combo, we will start with set rotation and shield, again lets pretend we dont have ankh in our starting hand)

1) activate set rotation to search either wedju temple or village of the spellcasters, for this combo lets choose village of spellcasters and our opponent gets wedju temple

2) set village on face down on your side and wedju face down on opponents side

3) activate shield from hand to s/t zone, pay 2000 LP to summon to field, shield effect to add ankh to hand

4) summon ankh, reveal 5 pieces of exodia to fusion exodia incarnate, ankh then shuffles back into deck

5) activate village face up, end turn, exodia effect to set exodd fires of rage face down

*if obliterate blaze is already set face down this turn, activate on your following turn to destroy your entire back row and add all 5 pieces of exodia in the back

combo 3 ( for this combo lets start of with instant fusion and heart of the blue eyes)

1) activate instant fusion to fusion summon millennium eyes restrict

2) activate heart of the blue eyes, send to GY to grab ankh from deck to hand

3) activate ankh, reveal all 5 pieces of exodia to go into exodia incarnate, ankh then shuffles back into deck

4) set whatever spells or traps you need to set face down (if you have obliterate blaze in starting hand, even better)

5) end turn, exodia effect to set exodd rage of fire face down

*if heart of the blue eyes is in GY remember to use its GY effect, and if obliterate blaze is set face down this turn, activate on your following turn, destroy your back row to add all 5 pieces of exodia in your back row to power up incarnate and swing for game

combo 4

*if you have 5 pieces of exodia in your starting hand, reveal to opponent and its ggs 🤣

Do you love dragons and value? This deck has you covered. From easily making Sheou and at times two. Making Dark Magician and Blue Eyes cry over banishing because they didn't treasure their normal monster we have Bystials. Fun fact did you know Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon was secretly a dragonmaid? Just show em Duality and be surprised. Some how even Jack and Yusei brought some cards for this list. Although the dark and twisted side of Sheou could not help but be Bystial Dis Pater for an extra attack by once again Duality. Ever face down an annoying boss monster give it a bounce by a Seal or let the Dragonmaids Tidy it on up. Suprising still strong and rewarding to learn. Cleaning up duels can still be nice.

deck_name: Rank 1 XYZ / Level 1 Board Swarm (2025 Update)
deck_description:
I'll update this for realsies later

Strategy:

For starters, the main strategy is to dump as many Lv.1's as possible on the board early to go into F0:Utopic Draco Future.

If you brick, then attempt to churn through the deck Magical Mallet or Card Destruction while leveraging the defensive cards to set up a board with more favorable conditions.

Sometimes though, you will get lucky and draw into some cards that facilitate the deck's gimmicks (Number 99: Utopia Dragonar, AA-Zeus, etc.)

 

Most Notable Lv.1 monsters:

Jester Confit, Turbo Booster, and Big One Warrior are free (for the most part) special summons.

Kinka-byo is basically the only monster you want to normal summon if you have to.

Evil Thorn can be a great extender alongside Kinka-byo; and also a uniquely optimal One for One target. 

Treeborn Frog is Treeborn Frog; dump it in the GY with either foolish burial or Big One Warrior.

Boss Monsters:

'Number 99: Utopic Dragon': another significant beater. First summon Utopia Roots then use a Rank-up-magic to bring this guy.

'Number 99: Utopia Dragonar' + 'Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy'/'Number 97: Draglubion'/'Number 92: Heart-Earth Dragon': Great little combo with the Hyper Rank up magic that works going first or second depending on summoning line.

'F0: Utopic Draco Future': This is a retrain of the original F0 and is not reliant on a Rank-up-magic; this is brought out with the two Slacker Magician XYZs, next summon F0:Utopic Future, lastly bring out F0:Utopic Draco Future.

'Number 100: Numeron Dragon': Finisher XYZ, akin to Borrelsword with the damage it is capable of.

'Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder': This guy is just mean. If you swarm the board, go into the Lyralusc XYZ, and then attack directly to satisfy the conditions to bring out AA-Zeus.

Categorizing the Main Deck:

 

Openers: 3x Big One Warrior, 3x Kinka-byo, 3x Evil Thorn, 3x Where Arf Thou?

 

Extenders: 3x Turbo Booster, 3x Jester Confit, 2x Jack in the Hand, 1x Instant Fusion, 1x Scapeghost, 1x Scapegoat, 1x One Day of Peace, 1x One for One, 1x Monster Reborn, 1x Card Destruction, 2x Magical Mallet, 1x Foolish Burial, 1x Treeborn Frog

 

Defensive Cards: 1x Ghostrick Dullahan, 3x Battle Fader, 1x Vijam, 1x Rainbow Kuriboh

 

Non-Engine Reqs: 2x Hyper Rank-up Magic: Utopiaforce

 

Mid/Late-game Bombs: 1x Rank-up Magic: The Seventh One, 1x Dystopia the Despondent

 

 

Categorizing the Extra Deck:

 

Instant Fusion Target: 1x Thousand-eyes Restrict

 

'Rank-up Magic: The Seventh One’ Targets: start with 1x No.101: Silent Honor Ark, into 1x No.C101: Silent Honor DARK, finishing with 1x Full Armored CRYSTALZERO Lancer

 

Rank 1 # XYZ + ‘Rank-up Magic’ Targets: start with 1x No. 39 Utopia Roots, finish with 1x No.99: Utopia Dragonar + 1x No.99: Utopic Dragon

 

Generic Rank 1 XYZ: Start with two of the following (1x Slacker Magician, 1x Ghostrick Dullahan, 1x Sylvan Princess), go into 1x F0: Utopic Future, finish with 1x F0: Utopic Draco Future

 

5 Materials on Field: start with 1x Assembled Nightingale, finish with 1x AA-Zeus

 

 

Notes:

 

- A combo line that exists in the sideboard and represents a decent finisher is as following: Summon "Number 97: Draglubion" with "Number 99: Utopic Dragonar", and use "Hyper-Rank-Up-Magic Utopiforce's" Graveyard effect to attach it to "Draglubion". Then, you can use "Draglubion's" effect to summon "Number 100: Numeron Dragon". "Numeron Dragon's" effect will result in it having 21,000 ATK.

- I plan to eventually add in a more robust 'combos' section

- I will modify the deck/extra deck/side deck over time into a more refined form

Any suggestions, constructive or otherwise, are appreciated

deck_name: Metalmorph/Mimighoul FTK with Assault Mode Engine
deck_excerpt: Fun Casual Deck with the power to FTK.
deck_description:
About a year ago some cards came into my mind that did a funny loop. Red-Eyes Metal Flare Dragon and Beelze of the Diabolic Dragons have mandatory effects that trigger a legal infinite which i thought was quite funny.

But I never found a good deck that could pump out beelze and Metal Flare Dragon. Until the new Metalmorph cards came out and flame swordsman had the same mandatory burn effect. So i started testing some engines together and funnily enough Mimighoul can pump out cards to make saryuja (to get rid garnets and better bricks) and it also is a good floodgate to either stall out the strategy or also force the opponent to trigger the strategy. It's also a great way to give your opponent Beelze with Geonator trasverser (because they don't need to be face up cards).

I really like this deck and if someone can help me make it better then please tell me! Also I don't like playing Handtraps in this deck because it kind of lives from the extenders but im open for possibilities.

deck_excerpt: Adventurer engine is still alive baby!
deck_description:
Deck profile and explanation :

Main:

3x Engraver: The 1 card Fiendsmith combo, and by far its most important card. 

1x Lacrima: 1 card Fiendsmith combo. 

1x Lurrie: A key part of the Fiendsmith combo. You add it and discard it by Tract, summon it from the GY with its own effect and then link it of into Requiem. 

3x Enchantres: 1 card adventurer combo. 

1x Gryphon: The adventurer combo's omni negate. 

3x Diabellstar: The Azamina combo starter. 

1x Diabelleze: If you have in your hand after you finished your Azamina combo, it can be a brutal floodgate for the opponent. Otherwise just discard fodder, but still pretty good. 

3x Nibiru: The most important hand trap against decks like Ryzeal, Maliss, Branded, Fiendsmith, Fire King etc. 

3x Veiler: Could've just played two since imperm does the same better, but still really good against Ryzeal which needs to be handtrapped multiple times to be finished off for good. 

3x Ash Blossom: The best hand trap of all time. 

1x Ogre: Again, you can just remove it since it is the weakest hand trap here, but still can come in clutch against decks that can summon bosses even after multiple hand traps. 

1x Mourner: Veiler on a diet. Can also be used for some burn damage if you use Ogre on the same monster. 

3x Tract: You almost always side for one. It can be used as a Fiendsmith starter, but is still better for being searched by Engraver and then doing the lurrie shenanigans. 

3x Aramesir: The 1 card starter and THE MOST IMPORTANT card in the Adventurer engine. 

1x Faithful Adventure: A key piece in the Adventurer combo, you search it off of Aramesir and then use it to search for Gryphon

1x Dracoback: I didn't use it a single time. Just side it out. 

1x Called by: Your saving grace if you get hand trapped in an important spot. 

3x Deception: A key combo piece for Azamina. 

3x Wanted: The 1 card combo starter for Azamina. 

1x Hallowed: The most important card for the Azamina engine. 

1x Paradise: a good way to set up your Fiendsmith combo during your opponent's turn, otherwise side it out. 

3x Imperm: The third best hand trap in the game (After Ash and Fuwalos). Also can't be Called by. 

1x Azurune: Bunny

Extra:

Sequence: Used if you go for Des Irae instead of Caesar in your Fiendsmith combo. 

Requiem: A key piece in the Fiendsmith combo, whether you go for Caesar or Des Irae. 

Moon: Can turn any two bodies in the field into a fiendsmith combo. 

Masquerena: Alright, I guess? It's not used in any of your combos, but can be good if you get handtrapped multiple times and can't continue to summon S:P during opponent's turn to banish thier bosses or starters. 

Little Knight: The best link monster in the game. Already explained.

Rabbit: If you can't continue and have two bodies on the floor, this little bunny is potentialy your only saving grace. 

Des Irae: Can negate multiple monstars if you do go for him, but kinda clunky to set up. 

Necroquip: idk honestly, I guess it can be used(?), but I didn't know. 

Aerial: idk man. Guess it can set up a Fiendsmith combo but I don't actually use it. 

Mu: Very good Azamina card. You can go without her but she's still good sometimes. 

Silvia: The omni negate of the Azamina combo. Insanely strong. 

Caesar: The main anti-Nibiru monster on the field. It can be used either as a summon negate to mess with your opponent or as a material for ZEUS and/or TY-PHON. 

Evolzar: A pretty good monster negate, but Caesar is still a bit better. 

ZEUS: If you went second, you can summon it on top of Caesar in your MP2 to make an insane boss monster and further ruin your opponent's chance of making a comeback in turn 3.

TY-PHON: The best Xyz monster in the game. It not only has a good removal effect, but it can also render all of your opponent's bosses useless and make them pretty much just big beatsticks. 

Deck pros and cons:

Pros: The deck has three engines which are all 1 card combo (omni)negates, and all can summon that one negate in under 5 special summons, so you're completely Nibiru-proof.

Cons: The three engines have no way of searching each other out, so if you want to go with all three combos, you need three special cards in your hand.
All is explained in the video. I just added some cards for help.
TBA for the description, I'm still working on it.
Still deciding what names each character gets.

Wight deck using some mill tricks from Lightsworn / Paleo / Dinomorphia decks. Inspiration for deck came while I was playing a 60-card, going second OTK build of Skull Servant and realized how crazy the mill off of wightlord is.

Initially thought about trying to use the wightlord mill as an engine for paleo but quickly realized the two builds don't have a ton of synergy and wightlord as a really effective mill engine would probably be too big for paleo.

So instead tried to do the reverse and use some tricks from Paleo/Dinomorphia decks involving transaction rollback to maximize the effectiveness of the wightlord mill. Saw a lightsworn / skull servant hybrid deck that had a similar idea but it didn't have enough ways to start the skull servant mill. This build is still a WIP but being able to trigger elemental burst via transaction rollback and swinging in with King of the Skull Servants right after has been crazy. Also wanted to keep the budget down which is why there's no horus engine. Think swapping out some of the more expensive traps (Ex. The Black Goat Laughs) might also be helpful.

Beyond the Pendulum searches Mistva, and the Melodious package gives one card combos into Beyond the Pendulum to search out Mistva and have a scale to perform a Pendulum summon. After an initial Melodious engine combo to set up an I:P and (if negation doesn't shut it down) a Vortex Dragon, the Ryu-Ge combo can step in for the second half to give way to Varudras negate and Mistva backed up by Continuous Spells. Eschatos and Mistva are both searchable off of Melodt of Awakening Dragon, so the Ryu-Ge combo can go into Reprodocus to change a searched Eschatos into whatever Type is needed to counter the opponent's deck, with game 1 knowledge being attainable thanks to Emva's on field effect with Sea Spires to banish the opponent's hand and redraw to see what they are playing.

deck_excerpt: Fiendsmith Ryzeal  / San Diego WCQ Regional Top 8
deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Kenneth Li

Tournament: San Diego WCQ Regional – December 21st 2024

Placement: Top 8

Testing out the newly announced Mitsurugi in everyones favourite reptile deck Ogdoadic supplimented with some Ragnaraika.

The Ragnaraika synergy mainly focuses on making the link-5 stag sovereign by way of the link-4 chain coils, for ED interuption and resummoning chain coils with futsu no mitami on the opponents turn likely through Mitsurugi prayers summoning it from grave.

So far the deck feels really fun, lots of interaction on the opponents turn with ok effects that pile up as you swarm on their turn. Obviously the deck dies to GY hate

Main plays include Ame no Murakumo and great purification for a 2ish negates, futsu no mitami for a board wipe, and standard ragnaraika with hunting dance, stag sovereign, and chain coils.

The Mitsurugi cards have a great ability to amass resources with all monsters having an effect on tribute and the ability to ritual summon from deck usually resulting in a +2 from the tributed card and summon of a ritual which can be chain blocked with the various quick play spells. So the deck has descent tools going second too.

Still considering ratios but 2 of each ritual seems good since you can tribute one for the ritual summon of itself from deck and/or hand.

This deck is able to go to blind 2nd so when losing the dice you are alright.

The purpose was to easily reach any fiend package by reducing the unplayable cards. This is the reason why I have removed sarama which is not that bad but you definitly prefer to normal summon a light fiend instead since those are a one card combo.

Abominable can be cut but he brings some added value because you easily trigger a destruction to summon it to extend your combo or destroy an opponent card. 

The trap unchained are good but not in this deck since they are useless if you don't draw any unchained monsters. This is why I added a foolish burial to give flexibility. If you have an unchained standalone card, just send shyama in GY to full combo or if you have only an unchained monster send sharvana to set a card.

I didn't added lurrie for the fiendsmith package because you always find value to discard a card like shyama or engraver for instance.

This deck is strong because you have the possibility to stop the opponent thanks to all the handtrap in the deck and with the fiend monster usually you will be able to destroy the opponent board. 

I still add budget because this is the best version I found with only 1 engraver. Obviously if you can add 2 engraver

Playing style[edit]

The archetype is geared towards a Link Monster beatdown strategy, with the Pawns supporting the Queens with protections.

Each Main Deck member of the archetype has effects that allow you to gain benefits by banishing another "Maliss" card from the hand, with the banished monster being able to Special Summon itself back to the field at the cost of 300 Life Points each. The Link Monsters further this strategy by continuously banishing both players' cards.

Other existing Cyberse monsters that benefit from being banished include "Dotscaper", which can Summon itself upon being banished, and "Balancer Lord", which allows the player to Summon another card from their hand.

Umi is a series of cards focused around the Field Spell Card "Umi". The core of the series is a group of Field Spell Cards that are "Umi" or are always treated as "Umi". The series features multiple supporting cards who have effects revolving around having a face-up "Umi" Field Spell.

In the Yu-Gi-Oh! anime, Mako Tsunami used a WATER Deck that utilized the Ocean terrain and later the "Umi" Field Spell, and has been informally associated with the "Umi" card series.

deck_excerpt: It's the fastest deck to farm the Tryout Duel - 2025 LP event!
deck_description:
Use a wide arsenal of burn cards to quickly defeat opponents! The hand traps Hanewata, Junkuriboh, Eco, Mystical Spirit of the Forest, and D/D/D Rebel King Leonidas counter the opposing burn decks!

On Soul of Fire

Soul of Fire is this deck's strongest burn spell. Two copies of this card can easily defeat opponents. With its effect, you can banish Subterror Behemoth Ultramafus to deal a huge 1500 points of effect damage and banish Morphtronic Datatron to deal 600 effect damage. Ultramafus is the cheapest main deck pyro monster available with a high attack stat. Datatron is the second preferred pyro monster, because it has a decent attack stat and a useful effect that deals 600 effect damage by tributing a monster. 600 damage is important because there are rare scenarios that need the extra damage. For example: Tremendous Fire + Goblin Thief = 1500 damage. Add in Datatron's effect damage, then it becomes 2100, enough for an otk. An alternative to Datatron is Volcanic Slicer, whose effect deals only 500 damage, which isn't enough to otk.

Some Tips

Soul of Fire can increase Restructer Revolution's damage by giving your opponent an extra draw.

D/D/D Rebel King Leonidas is an excellent counter to burn decks because his effect prevents his controller from taking any further effect damage. You can special summon King Leonidas from your hand by first damaging yourself with Tremendous Fire.

The 12 hand trap count increases your odds of drawing 2 hand traps in your opening hand. King Leonidas and Eco, Mystical Spirit of the Forest, and Hanewata prevent you from taking effect damage for the rest of the turn. Junkuriboh negates and destroys only 1 card that inflicts effect damage, but it can stop the opponent from getting too crazy by supporting the other hand traps.

Been using a Cyber Dragon Deck for years but in recent times it has become my favorite deck off all time! This is my take on the Cyber Dragon OTK with the added Cyberdark Chimera and Clockwork Knight combo with its release in the TCG in January 2025. The side deck contains cards i have found useful in playtesting this deck online but these are obvioulsy depended on your preferences. 

The new support cards for Cydra being the new Cyber Jormungandr and Cyberdark Wurm have only just been announced so i havent tried these new cards. I will be interested to see just what these cards do for the deck. Disablaster is quite literaly a 'Negation Fortress'! Negateing anything in the same column as itself is a blessing! either being able to be used with Machine Duplication to XYZ summon into Infinity or activate to shut down the opponents Pendulum Zone.

Cyberload Fusion and Cybernetic Overflow is a combo ive always been a fan off. Allowing you to pop opponents cards and quickly fuse into the Big Hitters and swing for the win! I've found in my play testing a single copy of CK is enough to pull the combo simply because my opponents dont know when to hit the combination, so it has always gone through! Cyber Dragons are very versitile and can use multiple different avenues to win the game, which is one of my favortie things about the deck. Cyber End Dragon and Cyber Twin Dragon are cards i use mainly for the Duality play with the Chimeratech's. 

I hope you enjoy my take on the Deck, Hail CYDRA!

deck_excerpt: Dogmatika Albaz en acción: Destruye el Extra Deck de tu oponente
deck_description:
presento un deck de Dogmatika Albaz diseñado para eliminar el Extra Deck del oponente de manera estratégica. La carta principal, Dogmatika Alba Zoa, es un ritual que nos permite enviar al cementerio una carta del Extra Deck del oponente por cada dos cartas que tenga. Si el oponente tiene 15 cartas en su Extra Deck, podemos eliminar la mitad.

La estrategia se basa en utilizar como carta clave a Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous, que nos busca la carta mágica Dogmatikamatrix. Esta carta no solo elimina una carta del Extra Deck del oponente, sino que también nos facilita reunir los recursos necesarios para invocar a Dogmatika Alba Zoa.

Además, contamos con Dogmatika Maximus, que nos permite enviar dos cartas de nuestro Extra Deck al cementerio para eliminar dos cartas del Extra Deck del oponente. Este efecto es aún más ventajoso para nosotros, ya que cartas como Elder Entity N'tss destruyen cartas del campo enemigo, y Herald of the Arc Light nos permite buscar cartas útiles.

Finalmente, para asegurar el control, tenemos a Dogmatika Fleurdelis, the Knighted, quien niega efectos de monstruos, puede ser invocado de forma especial y refuerza a todas nuestras cartas Dogmatika con 500 puntos de ATK permanentes durante la fase de batalla. ¡Este deck es ideal para dominar tanto el Extra Deck como el campo del oponente!

 

Aquí tienes las descripciones en español e inglés:

Español

En este video, presento un deck de Dogmatika Albaz diseñado para eliminar el Extra Deck del oponente de manera estratégica. La carta principal, Dogmatika Alba Zoa, es un ritual que nos permite enviar al cementerio una carta del Extra Deck del oponente por cada dos cartas que tenga. Si el oponente tiene 15 cartas en su Extra Deck, podemos eliminar la mitad.

La estrategia se basa en utilizar como carta clave a Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous, que nos busca la carta mágica Dogmatikamatrix. Esta carta no solo elimina una carta del Extra Deck del oponente, sino que también nos facilita reunir los recursos necesarios para invocar a Dogmatika Alba Zoa.

Además, contamos con Dogmatika Maximus, que nos permite enviar dos cartas de nuestro Extra Deck al cementerio para eliminar dos cartas del Extra Deck del oponente. Este efecto es aún más ventajoso para nosotros, ya que cartas como Elder Entity N'tss destruyen cartas del campo enemigo, y Herald of the Arc Light nos permite buscar cartas útiles.

Finalmente, para asegurar el control, tenemos a Dogmatika Fleurdelis, the Knighted, quien niega efectos de monstruos, puede ser invocado de forma especial y refuerza a todas nuestras cartas Dogmatika con 500 puntos de ATK permanentes durante la fase de batalla. ¡Este deck es ideal para dominar tanto el Extra Deck como el campo del oponente!

English

 I showcase a Dogmatika Albaz deck designed to strategically dismantle the opponent's Extra Deck. The key card, Dogmatika Alba Zoa, is a ritual monster that allows us to send one card from the opponent's Extra Deck to the graveyard for every two cards they have. If they have 15 cards, we can eliminate half of their Extra Deck.

The strategy revolves around using Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous as a key card to search for the spell Dogmatikamatrix. This spell not only removes a card from the opponent's Extra Deck but also helps us gather all the resources needed to summon Dogmatika Alba Zoa.

We also have Dogmatika Maximus, which lets us send two cards from our Extra Deck to the graveyard while forcing the opponent to do the same. This effect benefits us more, as cards like Elder Entity N'tss destroy enemy cards on the field, and Herald of the Arc Light lets us search for key cards.

To maintain control, we include Dogmatika Fleurdelis, the Knighted, who negates monster effects, can be special summoned, and boosts all our Dogmatika cards with a permanent 500 ATK increase during the battle phase. This deck is perfect for dominating both the opponent's Extra Deck and their field!

deck_excerpt: Most cancerous deck I have ever played
deck_description:
The goal is to get out "Morphing Jar" and flip it up and down multiple times to generate ressources and to deck out your opponent. 

You can get this card with two options.

Option 1: Lonfire Blossom or Orphys Scorpio

Lonefire into lonefire into lonefire into orphys scorpio, orphys scorpio eff discard one monster and then into darlington cobra, darlington cobra eff to add instantfusion.Then orphys scorpio and darlington cobra for link summon cross sheep. Activate instantfusion and summon master of ham into a zone cross-sheep points to. Eff 1 master of ham and eff 2 cross-sheep. Cross-sheep brings back lonefire and master of ham gets you morphing jar from your deck in face-down. Then lonefire one more time into another orphys scorpio. Then use cross-sheep, orphys scorpio and master of ham to link summon borrelguard dragon. Borrelguard dragon eff to flip up morphing jar and you are good to go

Option 2: You need to special summon 2 level 4 monsters, make gallant granite and use it's eff to add morphing jar to your hand, now you can set it. Then you need either a/d changer or book of taiyou or another 2 level 4 monsters to make photon papilloperative to flip up morphing jar.

Option 3: Spirit of the fall wind gets you also into morphing jar and in combination with double summon you can set it afterwards. Or even sometimes you draw it with the danger monsters.

 

This deck sucks against droll and lockbird, but it beats ash blossom, effect veiler, impermanence and even nibiru. Wish you great luck with this evil build.

The Ryu-Ge cards are the Awkward third Child of Crossover Breakers, while not strictly bad, they do not have the power level of Maliss' incredible high ceiling combo potential or Ryzeal's high impact, low to the ground lines.  Ryu-Ge is best served supplementing other decks, mainly Voiceless Voice.  the biggest benefit of VV as a shell for Ryu-Ge is that Saffira and Skull Guardian can search any Light Dragon Ritual monster, which includes Ryu-Ge's main starter Mistva.  So you go through you normal VV setup, then use Skull Guardian to grab Mistva, which then bridges the 2 combos and lets you do Ryu-ge setup under Skull Guardian's Omni-Negate.  From there you scale Mistva and pop it to get War Zone which will add Bahrastos and banish Emva send Kaiva (remember War Zone locks you into the dino Quad type, so if you want to do Mondo stuff you need to do so before resolving this).  War Zone will then summon Emva, Kaiva and Hakva  then Bahrastos will pop Emva and one other Ryu-Ge to summon itself which will cause Mistva to summon itself and place 2 Ryu-Ge Continuous Spells by poping Bahrastos and War Zone, usually including Wyrm Winds, which is a Dimensional Fissure on the opponent's turn, then can either keep the Ryu-ge Monsters to get the inherited effects or go into Varudras.

the ED has a target for each Ultimate Slayer target type, N'tss, Arc Light, Aggregator and Ferrijit, all generate additional advantage when sent, Arc Light and Arc light also serve as Diviner targets.  Otherwise its just the usual pile of utility peices you see in VV ED.  the Side is mostly the usual suspects in the current meta and Fuwalos, if you want to save some cash Fuwalos can be replaced with something like Eclipse or Bystials.

Overall this isn't a top tier contender, especially with weaknesses to both Shifter and Lancea, but its still a solid tier 2-3 type deck that should be accounted for.

Burning magic is a great card for a non-targeting board clearer and to this day, it has never been stopped when i personally have used the card.

 

Hope you enjoy the Deck!

deck_excerpt: Crystal Beasts with compact engines to make shenanigans take place regardless of circumstance.
deck_description: Crystal Beasts with compact engines to make shenanigans take place regardless of circumstance.

deck_excerpt: Yet another silly deck. (Based off of  @crimsonlafiamma's deck, look at their deck at  @crimsonlafiamma)...
deck_description:
Hello, Welcome!

It has been a while. How've y'all been? Anyway, straight into the guide, this deck uses a one card combo starting with T.G. Rocket Salamander to get to a point with 2 level 2s and a link monster to then branch off into multiple combos and variations mainly using sprights. Also this deck took alot of inspo from @crimsonlafiamma, thank you!

Let's start off by talking about the different engines:

T.G. Stuff:
    - 3xT.G. Rocket Salamander 
    - 1xT.G. Screw Serpent 
    -+ as many ways you want to search salamander(E.g. Bonfire or One for One)

T.G. Rocket Salamander is a one card combo, as previously stated, that allows us to land on any board Nimble Beaver can do (a link 2 and 2 level 2s) but without using their effects. It's only used for summoning Ib the World Chalice Justiciar.

World Chalice stuff:
    - 3x Crowned by the World Chalice
    - 2-3x World Legacy - "World Chalice" 
    - 1-2x Lee the World Chalice Fairy 
    - 1-2x World Chalice Guardragon 
    - 1x World Legacy Succession 
    - 1x World Legacy's Sorrow 
Extra Deck:
    - 1x World Chalice Guardragon Almarduke
    - 1x Ib the World Chalice Justiciar 
    - 1x Lib the World Key Blademaster  
    - 1x Ib the World Chalice Priestess 
    - 1x Auram the World Chalice Blademaster 
    - 1x Imduk the World Chalice Dragon 
    - 1x Gravity Controller 

This is the bulk of the combo (before the sprights come in) since the unbanning of Ib the World Chalice Justiciar the T.G. Rocket Salamander has been possible (with credit to @crimsonlafiamma) combo time!:

1 Card combo with T.G. Rocket Salamander:

Get T.G. Rocket Salamander on field > Tribute itself; summon T.G. Screw Serpent from the deck (yes T.G. Screw Serpent is a garnet) > on summon T.G. Screw Serpent summons back T.G. Rocket Salamander, negating its effects > synchro both T.G. Screw Serpent and T.G. Rocket Salamander into Ib the World Chalice Justiciar in the extra monster zone (otherwise th combo wont work) > Ib the World Chalice Justiciar triggers on summon, to add World Legacy - "World Chalice" to your hand > link Ib the World Chalice Justiciar into Gravity Controller (for a downwards pointing arrow) > when Ib the World Chalice Justiciar is sent from the field to the GY, it can summon Crowned by the World Chalice (or any normal "world chalice monster) > link the normal monster into Imduk the World Chalice Dragon > Imduk the World Chalice Dragon allows us to normal summon another "world chalice" monster, tribute the Gravity Controller to normal summon the World Legacy - "World Chalice" > ... This goes onto many variations, usually starting off by linking the 2 into a link-2 monster.

This is the "bread and butter" combo allowing us to branch off into many different variations. However I'll talk about them later.

Sprights(I did promise a spright deck) + nimbles and melffy(because I like the cute animals):
    - 1-3x Spright Blue 
    - 1-3x Spright Jet 
    - 0-2x Spright Red 
    - 0-2x Spright Carrot 
    - 2-3x Nimble Beaver 
    - 1-2x Nimble Angler 
    - 0-1x Melffy Catty 
    - 0-1x Melffy Pinny 
    - 1-3x Spright Starter 
    - 0-2x Spright Smashers 
    - 1x Spright Double Cross
Extra deck:
    - 1-2x Gigantic Spright 
    -1x Spright Sprind
    - 0-1x Melffy of the Forest

These allow us to establish a board and, (somewhat) play around Nibiru, the Primal Being by keeping our extenders like Spright Starter in hand, incase we hard draw into it (even if it's a %33.5 ish to draw).

continuing off from earlyer, COMBO TIME!:

we landed on a board containing Imduk the World Chalice Dragon and World Legacy - "World Chalice".

Link off Imduk the World Chalice Dragon and World Legacy - "World Chalice" into Auram the World Chalice Blademaster > (if you have any "world chalice" monsters in hand Imduk the World Chalice Dragon can summon themfor an extra body otherwise,) World Legacy - "World Chalice"  can summon out any 2 "world chalice" monsters except itself > let's summon Lee the World Chalice Fairy and Chosen by the World Chalice for this
combo > Lee the World Chalice Fairy can add another World Legacy - "World Chalice" (for next turn follow up) > and since they're both level 2, overlay Chosen by the World Chalice and Lee the World Chalice Fairy for Gigantic Spright > detatch Lee the World Chalice Fairy from Gigantic Spright; to summon Spright Blue from the deck > Spright Blue triggers to add Spright Jet > special summon Spright Jet  > Spright Jet triggers on special summon to add a Spright Double Cross (interuption 1) > link Spright Blue and Spright Jet into Spright Sprind > Spright Sprind triggers on special summon, send a Nimble Angler to the GY > Nimble Angler effect in GY, summoning 2 Nimble Beavers from the deck > overlay both Nimble Beavers into Melffy of the Forest > detatch one material from Melffy of the Forest; add Melffy Catty from the deck to your hand (interuption 2) > link the Gigantic Spright and Melffy of the Forest into an I:P Masquerena (interuption 3) > use the detatched Lee the World Chalice Fairys effect in the GY to send the Spright Sprind to the GY (to free up space for the Spright Double Cross) or you can keep Spright Sprind so you still have the Auram the World Chalice Blademaster for next turn, BUT you'll need to think ahead because double cross won't be available untill you link into S:P Little Knight.

This end board ends on: I:P Masquerena, Melffy Catty (ready to make Herald of the Arc Light), and a potential steal using Spright Double Cross. Overall this board is just a basic spright endboard, but it can throw off your opponent. If you want to make this end board - just play a regualr spright deck.
It's (at least) %90 easier.

Another endboard (that sprights can't make) is:

Link off Imduk the World Chalice Dragon and World Legacy - "World Chalice" into Auram the World Chalice Blademaster > (if you have any "world chalice" monsters in hand Imduk the World Chalice Dragon can summon themfor an extra body otherwise,) World Legacy - "World Chalice"  can summon out any 2 "world chalice" monsters except itself > Lee the World Chalice Fairy(summoned to an arrow Auram the World Chalice Blademaster points to) and Chosen by the World Chalice  are summoned > Lee the World Chalice Fairy can add World Chalice Guardragon > Auram the World Chalice Blademaster can send Lee the World Chalice Fairy to the GY; summon Ib the World Chalice Justiciar > use Lee the World Chalice Fairys effect in the GY to discard World Chalice Guardragon; and add back Lee the World Chalice Fairy > banish World Chalice Guardragon; summon back Crowned by the World Chalice > link both Crowned by the World Chalices into Spright Sprind > Spright Sprind triggers on special summon, send a Nimble Angler to the GY > Nimble Angler effect in GY, summoning 2 Nimble Beavers from the deck > synchro summon F.A. Dawn Dragster using a Nimble Beaver and Ib the World Chalice Justiciar (interuption 1) > overlay the other Nimble Beaver and into Gigantic Spright > detatch a Nimble Beaver  from Gigantic Spright; to summon Spright Blue from the deck > Spright Blue triggers to add Spright Jet > special summon Spright Jet  > Spright Jet triggers on special summon to add a Spright Double Cross (interuption 2) > go into Melffy of the Forest using the 2 level 2s > detatch 1 to add a Melffy Catty  > link Gigantic Spright  and Melffy of the Forest into I:P Masquerena.

It's just the same combo but with different steps and ends with an extra spell/trap negate :3.

this time let's use World Chalice Guardragon Almarduke to clear our field and make space and help push for game (this time you need another "world chalice" monster in hand) Ill use Chosen by the World Chalice just to show you that this can be achieved by any extra body:

Get T.G. Rocket Salamander on field > Tribute itself; summon T.G. Screw Serpent from the deck (yes T.G. Screw Serpent is a garnet) > on summon T.G. Screw Serpent summons back T.G. Rocket Salamander, negating its effects > synchro both T.G. Screw Serpent and T.G. Rocket Salamander into Ib the World Chalice Justiciar in the extra monster zone (otherwise th combo wont work) > Ib the World Chalice Justiciar triggers on summon, to add World Legacy - "World Chalice" to your hand > link Ib the World Chalice Justiciar into Gravity Controller (for a downwards pointing arrow) > when Ib the World Chalice Justiciar is sent from the field to the GY, it can summon Crowned by the World Chalice (or any normal "world chalice monster) > link the normal monster into Imduk the World Chalice Dragon > Imduk the World Chalice Dragon allows us to normal summon another "world chalice" monster, tribute Imduk the World Chalice Dragon  to normal summon the World Legacy - "World Chalice" > Imduk the World Chalice Dragon effect in GY to summon Chosen by the World Chalice (or any extra body) > link World Legacy - "World Chalice" and the extra body into Ib the World Chalice Priestess > World Legacy - "World Chalice"  can summon out any 2 "world chalice" monsters except itself > as usuall we'll summon out Lee the World Chalice Fairy and Crowned by the World Chalice > Lee the World Chalice Fairy effect to add a World Legacy Guardragon > link the non-link monsters into Lib the World Key Blademaster > use Lib the World Key Blademasters effect to set  World Legacy's Sorrow  from the deck > Lee the World Chalice Fairy to send World Chalice Guardragon and add itself from GY to hand > banish World Chalice Guardragon; summon Crowned by the World Chalice from the GY > Ib the World Chalice Priestess and Chosen by the World Chalice can be linked off to make Spright Sprind > Spright Sprind triggers on special summon> Ib the World Chalice Priestess, when sent to GY, specials a "world chalice" monster fromhand > chain like so:
chain link 1 Spright Sprind
chain link 2 Ib the World Chalice Priestess 

                                                                                                           RESOLVE:
summon Lee the World Chalice Fairy > send a Nimble Angler to the GY > Nimble Angler effect in GY, summoning 2 Nimble Beavers from the
deck > tribute all 3 link monsters ( Gravity Controller, Lib the World Key Blademaster and Spright Sprind) to summon out World Chalice Guardragon Almarduke > and just freestyle the rest A.K.A spright stuff C: to end up on a slightly fuller board

NOTES:
=>All of these boards can end with at least an I:P Masquerena, and Melffy Catty (for Herald of the Arc Light) when you sucsessfully get a sprind on board.
=> World Legacy - "World Chalice" can banish itself next turn to add a World Legacy Succession, this can re-summon a link-2 "world chalice" monster as an extra body

Other engines you can play:(because I need to fill up the world count :/ )

Swap Frog --> Toadally Awesome:
    -3x Swap Frog 
    -1x Mirror Mage of the Ice Barrier 
    -1x Freezing Chains of the Ice Barrier
Extra Deck:
    -1x Toadally Awesome 
a small and sweet engine that can be used to nib-proof any combos, it functions as such:
normal summon (or special summon by discarding a WATER monster) Swap Frog > on summon it can send an aqua monster from deck to GY, send Mirror Mage of the Ice Barrier > Mirror Mage of the Ice Barrier adds Freezing Chains of the Ice Barrier when it's sent to the GY > activate Freezing Chains of the Ice Barrier, on activation you can summon back Mirror Mage of the Ice Barrier > overlay Swap Frog and Mirror Mage of the Ice Barrier into Toadally Awesome.

Nib-proof checklist:
under 5 summons - Yes
stops nib if over 5 summons - Yup

Combo is certified nib-proof C:

Adventure engine!:(I geuss it kinda fith the theme?)
    -0-3x Speedroid Terrortop
    -0-1x Speedroid Taketomborg 
    -1-3x Water Enchantress of the Temple 
    -1x Wandering Gryphon Rider 
    -1-3x Rite of Aramesir(play more than the amount of Water Enchantress of the Temple you have)
    -1x Fateful Adventure 
    -1x Dracoback, the Rideable Dragon
This is an option...
The combo is:

Activate Rite of Aramesir, special summon an adventure token and activate Fateful Adventure  from deck > special summon a monster; triggers Fateful Adventure, add Dracoback, the Rideable Dragon to hand > activate the 2nd effect of Fateful Adventure, add Wandering Gryphon Rider, discard Dracoback, the Rideable Dragon > Dracoback, the Rideable Dragon can equip from GY to the adventure token > since you control an adventure tokem, special summon Wandering Gryphon Rider.

This is great if you're going 2nd, in theory:
GOOD:
1 - you get a negate and bounce

BAD:
1 - you can't activate the effects of any normal summoned monsters(no more T.G. Rocket Salamander)
2 - if you ARE going 2nd you can be negated at any time stopping the combo at any time

Kashtira:
    -3x Kashtira Unicorn 
    -2-3x Kashtira Fenrir 
    -0-2x Scareclaw Kashtira
    -0-2x Kashtira Riseheart 
    -1x Kashtira Birth 
    -1x Kashtira Big Bang 
Extra deck:
    -1x Kashtira Shangri-Ira 
    -+ any rank 7s you want
    -+ any level 8 or 12 synchros (for T.G. Rocket Salamander and Ib the World Chalice Justiciar)
A moderate rank 7 engine that can be used for well... rank 7s while using the tuners we have to make some off-level synchros (+ F.A. Dawn Dragster can be used for rank 7s too... for follow up)

I don't really play kashtira so... try searching 'kashtira combos' on google (i stole this engine off of another deck by Hector Orellana's, YCS Vegas profile cutting the field spell and theosis)

Anyway thats about 2000 words, time for the conclusion. Overall this deck is a fun deck to play, the T.G.s and world chalice are surprisingly functional together and allowing Chosen by the World Chalice to bridge into sprights gives this deck a really fun and somewhat quirky playstyle(but then again this is sprights with extra steps). The 1 card T.G. Rocket Salamander combo is very imperssive and can make a decent end board. The variability of the deck keeps your opponent on their feet to predict what you're going to do next. HOWEVER this deck runs out of gas really quickly, and - much like some spright decks - uses far too many materials to play only 40 cards without burning out and I had to do ALOT of cutting and condensing to get this to 40 cards - so play more, also it's less of a chance to draw bricks(but it's far more painful when you do). This deck dosn't play many handtraps because it's too tight to change ratios. All that being said, play this deck how you want and let me know any other lines you find, it'll help others that wish to play this bizzare deck. Thank you for reading!! :3
-@dracob

deck_excerpt: Easily bring the Psychic End Punisher out with 5000+ attack. Budget option with no Horus engine.
deck_description: Easily bring the Psychic End Punisher out with 5000+ attack. Budget option with no Horus engine.

Ryu-Ge in Swordsoul feels somewhat off, its not bad and definitely raises the ceiling of the deck, but it doesn't incoperate nearly as well as the Tenyis, especially conisdering the upcoming Tenyi support in about a month.  Swordsoul being able to play under the Quad Type lock of Ryu-Ge being Wyrms is nice and lets Swordsoul not worry about Nibiru, its eternal nemesis, and Protos is a housewrecker as always, but the lack of the free special summons and less forcus on Graveyard effects means it doesn't feel as good.  The requirement to open Mistva or a way to it is an issue, so maxing on War Zone and Rising is a must compared to in something like Voiceless.  The Ryu-Ge cards definitely feel more powerful than the Tenyis and just the size of the bodies makes ending games much easier compared to that build.  There is room to cut the cost here, mostly cutting the Druiswurms, Ty-Phon and and the second Varudras which will bring things closer to $200 in total, so this can be an okay budget friendly build.  I'd still say VV is the better way to do Ryu-Ge since the 2 actually bridge pretty naturally (war zone searching Mo Ye is a thing, but you need an outlet planned to trigger Mistva to come out of ED to do so), while Swordsoul is probably better served waiting a few weeks for SUDA with the new Tenyis, but this is certainly a viable option for locals.  I'd notmally explain more, but its the usual level 8 and 10 suspects for Swordsoul along with typical staples and the Ryu-Ge package, there just isn't a ton to talk about as a result.

deck_excerpt: Experiment with this exiting Lava Golem and trap deck!
deck_description: This decks mains around using Lava Golem and Stealth Bird as monsters and the Mirror Force traps.

Activate Warzone, banish Kaiva, send Emva, and Add Master Peace. Activate Warzone and special summon Kaiva from Banish, Emva from grave, and Hakva from deck.

If you have Dino Domains on the field, spin it to pop a monster, special Mistva. Pop warzone + a card of your choice, place Dino Domains + Sea Spires.

Odds are you may have another continuous spell in hand from using the archetypal effect of swapping the monster for the spell at some point. Summon Master Peace using your final Ryu-Ge monster and your spell of choice, replace tributed spell with one in hand if able.

Congratulations, you now have at least 2 quick effect pops, a monster negate, a bounce, and 2/3 of a tower on field.

Alternatively:

Normal Diviner (this takes up your Master Peace summon) add Mistva, continue combo until all 3 monsters are on field, activate Kaiva pop effect, summon Mistva, pop Diviner + Warzone, place spells of choice, Rank 10 into Varudras. Congratulations, you now have a monster negate, bounce, perma nerf, and an omni negate/pop on board.

Another alternative if you're going first and you already have Mistva in hand is you can send El Shadoll Construct (or any level 8 fairy from Extra or Main deck) to make Diviner level 10 for additional rank 10 plays, or if you've been droll'd out of Warzone, potentially summon one of the Ryu Ge's via their own effects to at least get Varudras. This is untested and just an idea. Unfortunately there are no real good level 8 Fairy targets aside from Construct, and even then she only adds a Shadoll spell/trap from grave to hand. So not that great.

This unique take on the Voiceless Voice deck uses Azamina to defeat its strongest opponents: Dimensional Barrier and Bricking!

Deception of the Sinful Spoils allows you to tribute Diviner of the Herald from the hand, getting you a Lo from deck without having to Normal Summon.

Azamina Voiceless Voice is one of the few decks capable of triggering two of the strongest effects of Cross-Sheep , summoning a monster back from grave and trading off two draws.

An extra Diabellstar the Black Witch is no problem for this deck, as she is the perfect level to fodder off for a ritual summon.

Bricky ritual monsters and Trias Hierarchia can now be useful in more ways than one. The discard requirement for the Azamina engine is perfect for cleaning up your hand.
