deck_excerpt: And they told me Life Points don't matter...
deck_description:
After playing this deck in Master Duel for a while, this is the UPDATED VERSION of this: https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/it-s-time-to-smell-the-roses-534452

...although, it plays quite differently. 

As with the original deck, your main goal is to get to Rosalina, if you do not, you don't instantly lose... but you may have to seek one of the alternative win conditions or just hope your opponent bricks lol.

The Basic Combo

0) If no Rosalina BUT, you have Aroma Blend, use blend and set Humid Winds. Search Rosalina. Save the other effect for later.

1) Summon Rosalina, Or Lonefire Blossom into Rosalina [Or if you are lucky, One for One her]

2) Summon Laurel using her effect.

3) Link into Aromaseraphy Jasmine

4) Use Laurels effect, then Aromaseraphy Jasmine's effect to search for Rikka Princess [OR another further combo piece or alt win condition if you already have her in hand]

5) Use Princess's effect to summon herself. Use Jasmine's second effect. Special Summon Mardel. Cry if you drew it into your hand (though you should still have other plays). If you have Aroma Blend in hand and didn't use it to get Rosalina, you discard Mardel and set Blessed Winds instead. It will be awkward but it will continue the combo.

6) Mardel Effect, Search Aromage Mangoram [OR another further combo piece or alt win condition if you already have her in hand]

7) Link all monsters into Aromaslilith Rosemary. Use her effect to search Aroma Blend. If you already have it, get Aromaseraphy Angelica in hand. [OR another further combo piece or alt win condition if you already have her in hand.]

8) IF YOU HAVE OTHER AROMAGE MONSTERS, OR WAYS TO GET MORE, DO SO NOW. Perform Step 0. If not possible, skip this step. 

9) Through any method availible, gain LP (Either with one of the tuners in hand or Humid Winds second effect. ENSURE YOU END THIS STEP WITH MORE THAN 8000 LP or  A METHOD TO GET MORE LP. Activate Rosemarys effect. Special Summon at LEAST Aromage Mangoram. If Canacanga, a second Laurel or Jasmine is in hand, also special summon them. DO NOT SUMMON ONE OF THE LV1 TUNERS.

10) If you used Aromaseraphy Angelica's effect to trigger Rosemary, ignore the first part of this step. Activate Angelica, gain LP and trigger the mandatory effects of your Aromages. This can extend some plays on turn 2, or in the case of Jasmine, let you draw handtraps and alt win conditions. Then, special summon Angelica from the GY using it's own effect.

11) Synchro Angelica and Mangoram into Sweet Mangoram. Add Either Dried Winds or Blessed Winds to hand. I find that it depends on the scenario. Dried is an extra interupption, that can be played at a different time than your other mandatory Aromage LP gain trigger effects, while Blessed let you trigger the effects more consistently and let you resummon Aromages to counter Kaiju's and similar cards. 

12) Fusion Summon using Mardel and Laurel in GY using Aroma Blend's second effect. Summon Aromalilith Magnolia. Set any Traps you have in hand.

13) Extend your plays if you can. Aromage Jasmine will give you an Extra Normal Summon and if you used One For One, you didn't use your Normal Summon too. Also, if you summoned an extra plant somewhere down the line, you can link it and Rosemary into Benghalancer for an extra interupption.

14) On your opponents turn, activate Humid Winds and search one of the LV1 Tuners with hand effects. Be careful not to go under 8000 LP or else you turn off all of your plant monsters anti-targetting and anti-destruction. You should now have all the tools to interuppt and cancel opposing plays. 

EXTENSION/ALT WIN CONDITIONS

1) Cactus Bouncer - Can't be special Summoned, but you can search it or draw into it. Must be your last action if you summon it. It basically means your opponent can't summon anything lol. It's also your emergency win condition if you get interuppted a lot, since I have gotten Blend negated, then gotten the non-link jasmine on board and just summoned it and passed. 

2) Naturia Carmellia - Pick Sunflower or Vein depending on whether monsters or spells matter more to you. Send one to GY on summon, special summon it with Carmellias effect on your opponents turn for an extra negate. Unlike Bouncer, this can be Special Summoned, so an extra Lonefire Blossom can be turned into this. They can also help you get into your emergency/extender Synchros. If you need more damage on board, I've used vein with Sweet Mangoram and turned them into Periallis, which resummons Sweet Mangoram. Circle of the Fairies is also another way to get Cactus Bouncer on field with it's extra Normal Summon.

3) Rikka/Sylvan - Sylvan Dancepione is your emergency Link-2 if shit goes wrong. If the Link Jasmine gets negated... ruh roh, Dancepione can sometimes get you back on track or down another line of play... but its entirely luck. It does however, allow you to get 2 monsters to share a level, which can help with synchros and XyZ plays. Rikka Glamour meanwhile should always be your first play, usually searching princess unless you already have one. It's not vital, so negating it with Ash is fine, and if you have an extra princess, you can search an extender instead. Snowdrop, the rikka fairy is your last piece of interupption you can place on the field. If things go to shit, you can special summon her and another plant by tributing a negated plant. Then, much like Dancepione, she can get 2 monsters to level 8. With that you can make the Xyz that tributes on quick effect. Funny enough this is another way to get Naturias online too, since you can summon either Carmellia, or Lonefire Blossom with this. Eitherway snowdrop is a good extender and doesn't even need to use her second effect all the time since your Fusion monster is also level 8. If it's not doing anything... well there you go.

Oh and Rikka Petal? Thats an emergency way to get to Aromalilith Rosalina via the Rikka's Spell's second effect if you tribute a card. It's also an extender since it is also a searcher of Rikka stuff, so you can summon it instead of Mardel if... Mardel decides to be the brick that it is.

Effect Considerations

I have played the main combo and emergency other routes of play enough times to mention these. Don't forget these effects.

Need Emergency LP? - Aromalilith Rosemary has a third effect that lets you gain 1000LP in exchange for a monster it points too. It's usually not worth it on the main combo path, but it has come up a few times, especially on Turn 2.

BANISH - Aromalilith Magnolia can pay 2000LP to banish shit based on the number of Wind Traps you have. Note that you don't get to pick the amount you banish from this effect. This usually comes up when im the second player and need to scuff past stuff, since blend will ensure you always have at least 1 Wind Trap. That being said, this feels very much like a Turn 3 Clean-up effect. It is however, non-destructive removal, so keep it in mind. 

FIRE FIRE FIRE - Dried Winds second effect rarely comes up... but when it does it is spectacular because even people who read the card sometimes forgets it has a second effect. Also I have used it against Dinomorphia to limited effect.  

 

Closing Notes

I'll be honest, this deck folds a lot of the time to Rosalina -> Ash Blossom -> Cry. It's an obvious chokepoint and while there are ways around it, you either get a half-baked board, Cactus or death or... usually just Rosalina pass. It's never going to be meta and I hesitate to call this rogue, but I have had hilarious wins against Runick, Tenpai, Swordsoul Tenyi and other decks. 

Its fun. At least for me.

deck_excerpt: Domain Format: Budget Structure Deck Glow-Ups
deck_description:
You won't be able to stop this Burst Stream of Destruction! 
This is a beginner-friendly Domain Format list built upon a $11.99 purchase of the Structure Deck: Blue-Eyes White Destiny. It consists of a $10 upgrade of cards purchased from sites like TCGplayer. 

Deckmaster: Odd-Eyes Revolution Dragon 
Domain Restrictions: LIGHT // DRAGON // ODD-EYES
Made for Domain Format: Join the Community Discord!

To create this upgrade, please remove these 15 cards and any duplicate cards from the SD: Blue-Eyes (in the sidedeck): 

  • ydke://o6lXBdcanwHZjdIBn6bTA3gNPQOf+zsER7x9ALIyzAUx3BEBt4BNA4oMdAFgaA0BtXYOAa+h6AIBr8kEZ449BNCyQQFiarMDqniTAvSIZAM=!gZ1eA92drgDNQlcFUzZwAjXQkAMCXIIClrpzAQ==!6btLAjbHtQIqv/0DryPeACqVZQGD4MEEpyg7AdIjbgHmfiAAptD+AJIeIAKEqkUCPqRxAelfWQEiSJkA!
  • View on YGOprodeck
  • Structure Deck Full Contents (YGOprodeck)

Next, you will want to buy and add these 49 cards to the deck: 

  • ydke://WqrPAx0t6AL5EFgElqFUA06YSgVAAL8DNzEWA9pGsAS7+qgAreIKAlsBPwKts+oAei24BXZmVQRFkfoDUveKA2J8uAL3To0AYnVCBdZl6AL8/EAADfUMAaO8kQXjsCoD3xV7AsWp2gSQBiMAX2EFAibrAASGkmgA145WBVgv9wT5YBADok+KAKkqjQCbw3QBLHfWADZXLQAq7xgFQKXzAA==!1HOgAOYwAgIOniYAk41TAmpbIQHOAs0DWVWBBe1rFQU=!9NL4AA==!
  • View on YGOprodeck
  • View on TCGplayer Cart

Notably, this deck does not use Infinite Impermanence which is currently a pricy card at $7. Because Infinite Impermanence is included in the Structure Deck, you may choose to add it into the deck or sell it to fund the $10 purchase of cards you'll need. 

Additional Resources can be found here:
https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1c8_W7TLHoExz9Iq2yNBKG4kniKN3fjamfMVRehPRitQ/edit?usp=sharing

Domain Format General Rules:

  • Singleton Format: Every card restricted to 1 copy per deck.
  • 60-card Format: Each Main Deck must contain exactly 60 cards.
  • 4-player Pods: Each player competes individually in an all-out battle against three opponents.
  • Deckmaster Restrictions: Each player chooses a "Deckmaster" which dictates the allowed types and attributes for their deck.
  • Deckmaster Contract: A Deckmaster can be summoned from a designated "Deckmaster Zone" using normal summoning rules. After switching zones, Deckmasters may return to the "Deckmaster Zone," where they start the game.

Refer here for additional rules and exceptions:

https://www.domainformat.com/rules 

Broad Categories

This simple strategy has cards that fall into three simple categories:

  • Beatsticks
  • Searchers
  • Synchro/XYZ material

What do we want our Deckmaster to do? Odd-Eyes Revolution Dragon 

- Non-OPT Revival Spell for Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon and Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Dragon without negating their effects
- Ignore DM cumulative cost with Spell Economics 

The deckmaster Odd-Eyes Revolution Dragon is unconventional as neither a Blue-Eyes monster nor a starter for the Blue-Eyes deck. What it brings to the table however is unmatched, and is similar to the infamous card Soul Charge. Due to Odd-Eyes Revolution Dragon lack of a Once-per-Turn, we can repeatbly scale it from the Deckmaster Zone, revive a monster, then return it to the Deckmaster Zone to be scaled again. We are unintrested in its other 2 effects, and are equally uninterested in summoning it.

This becomes especially powerful when combined with another card without a hard Once-Per-Turn which is Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon to summon multiple Light Dragons from the Extra Deck while only needing to make Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon once. 

Another case where repeatble summons are useful is through revivals of Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Dragon and Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy. The Galaxy-Eyes XYZ monster have special conditions which allow them to be XYZ summoned using only another "Cipher" or "Galaxy" monster, of which we can fulfill by reviving Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Dragon. Galaxy-Eyes Full Armor Photon Dragon and Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Blade Dragon allow us to easily obtain 10200 attack on the board along with a steal, a pop, and another pop while only scaling and using Odd-Eyes Revolution Dragon twice after overlaying for Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Dragon.

However, where this Deckmaster is the most ridiculous is when paired with Spell Economics to ignore the cumulative cost of moving Odd-Eyes Revolution Dragon out of the Deckmaster Zone. By ignoring the cost to activate Odd-Eyes Revolution Dragon as a spell, we effectivily have inifinte revivals and link material. This allows us to efficiently summon Borrelsword Dragon alongside a full board of Blue-Eyes and Galaxy-Eyes XYZ and Synchro Monsters for a big push of damage. 

Odd-Eyes Revolution Dragon has great synergy with our Blue-Eyes extra deck, and gives the deck a fantastic recursion gameplan and endgame.

The Searchers

- Galaxy Satellite Dragon, Sales Pitch, Mythical Bestiamorph searches any card
- Draw the card on top with cards like Kingyo Sukui, Arrive in Light, Supply Squad, and Dark Factory of More Production  
- Find Maiden of White as a starter
- Obtain handtraps and Spell Economics / Swordsoul Punishment whenever you need it

Galaxy Satellite Dragon is a fantastic card in a rotation where there are 3 opponent's End Phases. To explot the ability to search any card 3 times, we will use the ability to draw cards on our opponent's turns using continous Spells and Traps such as Kingyo Sukui, Arrive in Light, Supply Squad, and Dark Factory of More Production. This ability to search any desired card will be extremely useful so we can break any board our opponent's may have, even if they require specialized tools like Jizukiru, the Star Destroying Kaiju.

In addition, the ability to search Spell Economics allows us to continue using our Deckmaster Odd-Eyes Revolution Dragon to grind even if low on life points.  

The XYZ/Synchro Material

- Maiden of White is the most important starter in the deck
- Rely on Galaxy cards to have 2 Lv.8 on the field for XYZ summoning

Maiden of White is so important, we dedicate many slots for searching Lv.1 monsters solely to find her. Maiden of White allows us to access True Light and summon Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon which are both core to the gameplan by accessing our Spells/Traps and Extra Deck respectivily. 

While this deck can easily have 1 lv8 monster in the form of Blue-Eyes White Dragon, we may struggle to summon out a second. This is why we have Galaxy lv8 monsters which summon themselves from the hand in order to supplement us.

Other Considerations 

Out of Budget: Crimson Dragon , Bystial Magnamhut , Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder , Arrive in Light , Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Primal 

Monsters: Dogmatika Nexus , Priestess with Eyes of Blue , Santa Claws , Ancient Fairy Dragon , Number 97: Draglubion , Number 100: Numeron Dragon , Lyna the Light Charmer, Lustrous , Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon , Black Dragon Collapserpent , Noctovision Dragon 

Spells/Traps: Jar of Avarice , Jack-In-The-Hand , Booby Trap E , Dragon Shrine 

Roar like a Dragon!

deck_excerpt: Branded has obtained a powerful new win condition - Light and Darkness Dragonlord!
deck_description:
With Masterduel's new selection pack "Dragon's Reincarnation," Branded has obtained a powerful new win condition - Light and Darkness Dragonlord!

Albaz and friends now has access to LADD Dragonlord's triple omni-negate, and this powerful card is easily summonable in the standard Branded combo!

As long as your opponent doesn't "ash" your Branded Fusion, you should be able to play through most handtrap your opponent throws at you and out-resource, our-grind, and out-muscle your opponent with multiple gigantic fusion boss monsters! Fuwalos, Purulia, Droll, Shifter and Maxx "C" are all easily brushed away with solid Branded gameplay!

If you want a thorough guide on this deck, check out my earlier article by clicking here.

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_excerpt: Maliss with Kashtira package, brought to Hartford regional 2025 7-2 Final Record 14th place
deck_description: Well, 1 last Maliss build i'm going to look at until ALIN arrives, Kash Maliss.  The idea is unicorn is in your hand around 50% of the time with 3 copies and 2 searchers, and while less verstile than Striker, it gives better lines into Lancea, allowing I:P into S:P setups that are harder to do with Striker since Kagari can't be used for I:P.  Main Deck shifter also fits much better here since Birth can retreive a banished Unicorn and just hoses Feindsmith builds.  Droll is the only hand trap that doesn't work under shifter here, but is so high impact it doesn't matter.  No Link Spider in extra since without the token i have less need of ways to get tokens into effect monsters since tokens are fair game for the Maliss Links, so the Nib token is less of a concern.  The big change to the ED is Knightmare Gryphon, an obnoxiously powerful, and typically one sided floodgate against activating monster effects, that if accessible can with the game on its own.  This deck has an incredible amount of gas, while maintaining adequate flexibility to beat many of its blowouts and still run 19 hand traps.  This is at present my favorite way to build Maliss.  The Side Deck is pretty typical, Lancea for the mirror with Sanctum as a thrust target going first.  Eclipse, Slayer and D Barrier for Ryzeal.  Droplet and Duster are just flexible cards that come up in different scenarios.

Also see my “Extreme Prog Banlist” Cube to see the currently banned cards. New Bans: Metalmorph and Giant Soldier of Stone

Playing style[edit]

"Thunder Dragon" revolves around Thunder monsters with discard, floating, and banish-activated effects, in order to set up resource recursion and summon conditions for boss monsters.

The archetype has 5 (relatively low-Level) Main Deck monsters with Levels under 6, who serve as combo pieces to bring out the archetype's boss monsters. Almost all of them have two effects: an Ignition Effect activated by discarding them, and a Trigger Effect that can be activated when they are banished or sent from the field to the Graveyard. These effects provide search power and field setup, and also sets up the GY with monsters for the archetype's other effects.

Of these monsters, "Thunder Dragonmatrix" is the only one under Level 4, making it the only one that can be Normal Summoned without Tributes.

"Thunder Dragon" boss monsters consist of both Main Deck Special Summon-only monsters ("Dragonduo" and "Dragonlord") and Extra Deck Fusion Monsters ("Colossus" and "Titan"). The former are summoned from the hand by banishing friendly cards in the hand/GY, while the latter are summoned with Fusion Summoning or pseudo-Contact Fusion.

On the field, the Main Deck bosses provide protection ("Thunder Dragonlord") or card resource cycling ("Thunder Dragonduo"), while the Fusion bosses provide removal/interruption ("Thunder Dragon Titan") or floodgating ("Thunder Dragon Colossus"). Each has one effect that banishes cards from the player's GY, possibly even in the opponent's turn, providing more triggers for "Thunder Dragon" banish effects.

"Thunder Dragon Fusion", the archetype's Fusion Spell, works with the archetype's discard and banish effects by Fusion Summoning through shuffling materials from the field, GY, or banished cards into the Deck. It can also banish itself from the GY (except on the turn it was sent there) to search out 1 Thunder monster, providing additional follow-up.

Because almost all "Thunder Dragon" non-boss monsters require setup/external combos to be summoned, their Trigger Effects are more easily triggered by banishing them. This can be achieved with:

  • Banish from Deck: "Gold Sarcophagus", "Aloof Lupine"
  • Banish from hand: "Allure of Darkness", Summon procedure of "Thunder Dragonlord", alternate Summon procedure of "Thunder Dragon Titan"
    • The alternate summon procedure of "Titan" can be established by using "Instant Fusion" or "Ready Fusion" to summon "Kaminari Attack"
  • Banish from GY: Summon procedure of "Thunder Dragonduo", Chaos series monsters, "Bystial" monsters

Generally, the Deck aims to turbo out one or more of its boss monsters, primarily (in formats where it's available) the high-power and easy-to-summon "Thunder Dragon Colossus", and back them up with other generic field presence and searchable follow-up. The Deck's main searchers are the banish/floating effects of "Thunder Dragondark" and "Thunder Dragonroar", while its main source of swarming are the effects of "Dragonroar" and "Thunder Dragonhawk".

deck_name: La Jinn the Mystical Genie of the Lamp
deck_excerpt: La Jinn the Mystical Genie of the Lamp
deck_description: La Jinn the Mystical Genie of the Lamp

Playstyle Tips

  1. Control Fate: Use Light Barrier and Second Coin Toss to ensure the heads effects of your Arcana Force monsters activate consistently.
  2. Tribute Summon Focus: Many of Sartorius’ monsters require Tributes, so cards like Celestial Transformation or The Emperor’s heads effect will help you summon them quickly.
  3. Stall and Build Power: Use cards like Arcana Force 0 - The Fool and Temperance to defend while setting up your strategy.
  4. Coin Toss Synergy: Cards like Lucky Chance and Reversal of Fate help capitalize on Sartorius' coin toss mechanics.

 

This deck captures Sartorius’ light manipulation and coin toss theme while maintaining a balance between anime flair and real-world playability.

deck_excerpt: Deck for people with no friends :)

deck_description: Very versatile deck; the first of its kind. The problem with Dream Mirrors was that it was known for being slow. As one of my favorite archetypes ever, I FINALLY found the solution: making the overall strategy revolve around the field spells, as well as wasting deck space on the Dream mirror spells and traps requiring either field spell on the field. Once you don't care about their strategies, they become a real threat. Pretty unorthodox but that's what makes this deck lethal. The Fiendmsith engine can be used on the Dream mirror fusions, and there is a hidden combo during the Battle Phase where you can fusion summon with their fusion card, which can give you an additional attack. Very aggressive on the field.

Fuse! Transform! Together we become something greater!
This is a beginner-friendly Domain Format list built upon a $11.99 purchase of the Structure Deck: Albaz Strike. It consists of a $10 upgrade of cards purchased from sites like TCGplayer. 

Deckmaster: Keeper of Dragon Magic 
Domain Restrictions: DARK // DRAGON 
Made for Domain Format: Join the Community Discord!

Disclaimer: Keeper of Dragon Magic does not encompass the LIGHT // SPELLCASTER domain, which locks us out of powerful Branded engines like Dogmatika and Cartesia 

To create this upgrade, please remove these 15 cards from the SD: Albaz (in the sidedeck): 

  • ydke://lmQjASsJtgLrvhQEd1uEARLRQgXeMuoFlqFUA2iItQGts+oAoXYGAG7oiAAAgiEBg+ykAqL7FQJPY7IDdltcAf4KgAQ+pHEBJpBCA9Ct3wQt3g4Bhd//AxZf1wTLS5ID!d56hAsRENAQuTncCNcATAnwYHQCI5joF!j/+kAGB09wQRYnEBs2euABImlAVm8f8BOFHvAjxDbgSyMswFUveKA36w6gSfOycEHS3oAlqiNQHhibAD!
  • View on YGOprodeck
  • Structure Deck Full Contents (YGOprodeck)

Next, you will want to buy and add these 45 cards to the deck: 

  • ydke://rvTMAq58cwSCS7kF2i1eAMWp2gSSKWMAvadvAdQnHABdad4CvgovAlh77gRy6u4FhvnIAfVTCABO93UBu/qoAAzglQBbAT8CjLuuAsa7wAOhcNwEiyIuAjM3GgLMHa0D4ZutAhakMgQYplQEpjCVAuCFBwJZlKcCCjRnAFzU8wFoXrECyRAmAaMvCAJuhjME!N8zzA0iIswC1TCsE8HIQA99phgGqEUECAb+sAE+baAAdCjQA!zindAg==!
  • View on YGOprodeck
  • View on TCGplayer Cart

Additional Resources can be found here:
https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1c8_W7TLHoExz9Iq2yNBKG4kniKN3fjamfMVRehPRitQ/edit?usp=sharing

Domain Format General Rules:

  • Singleton Format: Every card restricted to 1 copy per deck.
  • 60-card Format: Each Main Deck must contain exactly 60 cards.
  • 4-player Pods: Each player competes individually in an all-out battle against three opponents.
  • Deckmaster Restrictions: Each player chooses a "Deckmaster" which dictates the allowed types and attributes for their deck.
  • Deckmaster Contract: A Deckmaster can be summoned from a designated "Deckmaster Zone" using normal summoning rules. After switching zones, Deckmasters may return to the "Deckmaster Zone," where they start the game.

Refer here for additional rules and exceptions:

https://www.domainformat.com/rules 

Broad Categories

This simple strategy has cards that fall into two simple categories:

  • Recursion
  • Fusion

What do we want our Deckmaster to do? Keeper of Dragon Magic 
- Main Normal Summon
- Search Branded Fusion and Instant Fusion 
- Pull monsters like Dark Magician out of the GY to be used as Fusion Material (Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon)

Keeper of Dragon Magic provides a reliable access to any of our Fusion spells. The resolution of Branded Fusion is powerful by easily accessing our endboard piece of Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon through fusion summoning Lubellion the Searing Dragon. 

Instant Fusion accesses Predaplant Ambulomelides which provides fast access to Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra to extend our endboard further. Typically, this allows us to attempt to extend past disruption and add a Predaplant Dragostapelia to the endboard.  

Dark Magician is a card that be easily sent to the GY through Branded Fusion and is one half of a Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon. Dragoon is a powerful piece that is hard to remove and a useful beatstick.

What do we want our recursion to do? 
- Branded Regained gives us draw power and interaction with the banished pilr
- Branded Retribution recycles our Fusion monsters to be summoned again

Branded is a deck that can easily access many many cards. In order to ensure we do not run out of choices, recursion and recovery is an important aspect of the deck. Fortunetly, Branded Regained is one of the most absurd grindgame tools ever made. Branded Regained ability to recycle a LIGHT or DARK monster can be manually triggered through the cost of our cards like Black Dragon Collapserpent, Despian Tragedy, Chaos Dragon Levianeer in order to put choice cards back for reuse. 

When recycling, you want to put back cards that can be easily reused. Good choices include the fusions, especially Albion the Branded Dragon and Lubellion the Searing Dragon

What do we want our Fusions to do? 
- Control the Board
- Access our deck

Albaz fusions are well known for having GY effects in addition to their on-board effects. The most important of these GY effects is the effect of Albion the Branded Dragon to set a Branded spell/trap. In most cases, you would want to set Branded Banishment or Branded in Red in order to fusion summon a monster on your opponent's turn, whether that be Guardian Chimera or Masquerade the Blazing Dragon. 

The most powerful effect in our Extra Deck is Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon which not only sets up our other Fusion's GY effects, also non-target banishes a card on the field. Note that this effect is a soft-opt, so it can be used again if Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon is resummoned or revived. 

The core piece to all of these monsters is Fallen of Albaz himself. While Branded Fusion does provide easy access to Fallen of Albaz, it may be the case where we will want to manually summon these monsters. This is where our Deckmaster Keeper of Dragon Magic comes in handy to ensure we have access to Albaz even when it is in the GY. It is for this reason that we are running many Fusion effects in addition to The Bystial Aluber and Albaz the Ashen which treat themselves as "Fallen of Albaz" while in the GY.

Another mini-combo that can be done in the End Phase is with either Sprind the Irondash Dragon GY effect or Decisive Battle of Golgonda to summon Springans Kitt in order to add Branded in Red, immediatly activating it to Fusion Summon another endpiece Fusion monster.

Other Considerations: 

This is a rather simple decklist with minmal modifications, however Branded decks in the TCG are much more complex with many paths in part due to the addition of Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous and Guiding Quem, the Virtuous which can easily access Granguignol the Dusk Dragon or Synchro plays. It can be considered to modify this upgrade in order to obtain a Domain wide enough to encompass these strategies. However, I will not consider them in this section. 

Monsters: Shaddoll Dragon + El Shaddoll Winda , Thousand-Eyes Restrict , Magikuriboh , Guardragon Pisty , Tearlaments Havnis , Fantastical Dragon Phantazmay , Skull Meister , Mahaama the Fairy Dragon , Heavenly Zephyr - Miradora , The Bystial Lubellion 

Spells/Traps: Shaddoll Fusion, Ultra Polymerization , Pot of Avarice , Allure of Darkness , Nadir Servant , Fusion Conscription , Frightfur Patchwork , Ebon Sun , Spell Absorption , Soul Absorption , Crossout Designator , Book of Eclipse , Predaprime Fusion , Trap Tracks , New Frontier

deck_excerpt: This deck sucks, but if you can survive your first turn and loop the siren you're probably fine.

deck_description:
Deckmaster: Archfiend Eccentrick 
Domain Restriction: LIGHT // FIEND
Made for Domain Format

Join the Community Discord: https://discord.gg/3jRnBGHQJs 

 

The main idea of this deck is to use Reasoning and Monster Gate to mill a good chunk of the deck. Fiendsmith exists to make sure we have a board to survive until we can find these cards. Additionally, it can shuffle itself back into the deck, which is useful when we know for certain all our other monsters are out of the deck, but still want to mill.

Lacrima the Crimson Tears with Fiendsmith Engraver allows us to have an interrupt through Fiendsmith in Paradise sending Fiendsmith's Desirae. This makes Lacrima the Crimson Tears hard to handtrap because they would need to remove both the body and negate the effect.  

Great spells and traps to put into the GY are Runick and Paleozoic. Its fun to draw many cards with Runick Fountain and to have a lot of monsters on the board with Paleozoic.

A weakness of this deck is the lack of Light Fiends, especially because the deckmaster is a Pendulum monster that is not sent to the GY.

Inspired by https://youtu.be/ZzfbGdGLUS8?si=jlGx1sKBNuf87aaH    

The rest of the deck is boardbreakers. Archfiend Eccentrick contributes to this gameplan in addition to being able to Link-1 into Fiendsmith's Requiem 

Other Considerations:

Spell/Traps: Double Summon , Chain Summoning , Infinite Impermanence , Dominus Impulse , Dominus Purge , Angel of Blue Tears + Maiden of Blue Tears , Magical Explosion , Break Off Trap Hole , World Legacy Cliffhanger , Induced Explosion , Skill Prisoner , Destructive Daruma Karma Cannon , Royal Oppression 

Monsters: Beatrice, Lady of the Eternal + Fiendsmith's Lacrima , Aerial Eater + Constellar Ptolemy M7 , Muckraker From the Underworld , Unchained Soul Lord of Yama , PSY-Framegear Gamma + PSY-Framegear Delta + PSY-Framelord Lambda 

PSY-Framegear can be good if I had a Dark Factory of Mass Production or Boardwipe, but PSY-Frame Driver bricks the Monster Gate

This deck is still a work-in-progress, but the main idea is that the PSY-Frame monsters summoning Driver on the opponent's turn enables the Primite effects like Drillbeam, Scream, and Imperial Dragon. Extra deck is very flexible, just prioritze Lambda since it enables your PSY-Frames.

Some other misc synergies:

  • Lizardose -> banish Redox -> search Beryl
  • Lode/Roar summon Labradorite -> send to summon Lubellion
  • Foolish goods can send Overload, which can search either Circuit or a hand-trap, or Drillbeam, which can reset itself.
Evilswarm Blended W/ Bystial and Arc Rebellion Dragon

deck_description:
Maindeck:
Orcust but for the modern metagame. Includes a healthy amount of discard engines in order to ensure an Orcust lands in grave. Regardless, the addition of Galatea-i, the Orcust Automaton makes Orcust Harp Horror  a normal summon, allowing combo in a hand full of non-engine. In the past, Orcust builds playing Orcustrated Babel  have usually been fine through Nibiru, the Primal Being, however commiting to the Azamina line provides provides full protection through it. Additionallty, the inclusion of Enlilgirsu, the Orcust Mekk-Knight as the go-to boss monster keeps crescendo online during the opponents turn, as well as providing another piece of disruption. The deck plays around Mulcharmy Purulia very well (in the form of Diabellstar the Black Witch being an inherent summon), however plays horribly into Mulcharmy Fuwalos. Opening Orcust Crescendo isnt the worst thing in the world because Enlilgirsu can recycle it after using it to search Girsu, the Orcust Mekk-Knight. 

Sidedeck:
Plaing 3 Crossout Designator 1 Dimension Shifter because auto lose. Assorted going first floodgates. Going second gameplan is to just play through everything.

Playing 43 cards because of the amount of soft garnets/bricks.
Pure ryzeal, no fiendsmith, if no money for fuwaloss just replace with any other handtrap you want.

Example math for Equation Cannon: 
[ total number of cards on field and hand ] - [ level of opponent's targetable monster ] = [ XYZ rank ]
then,
[ level of opponent's targetable monster ]  - [ XYZ rank ] = [ Fusion level ]

Example:
Total number of cards on field and in hand: 11
Subtract level of opponent's targetable monster: 8
= 3
3 is the rank of the 2 XYZ monsters you send to GY.
Subtract rank of XYZ monster (3) from pponent's targetable monster (8)
=5
5 is the level of the fusion monster you send to GY.

deck_description: brainrot waifu deck with new cards. have no idea what final ratios are gonna be like
TCG NO AZAMINA, NO MULCHARMY, NO SPUER POLYMERIZATION, NO TRIPLE TACTICS TALENT etc. . . xd

Nearly two and a half years after its inception in Power of the Elements in the OCG/TCG, Tearlaments continues to be the metagame graveyard powerhouse! Historically being the strongest Yugioh deck of all time, Tearlaments has weathered the many banlists that targeted it, and it still remains a tier 1 meta threat to this day - especially on Masterduel ladder!

With the Horus cards Masterduel, Tearlaments have another way to mill cards to the GY with The Zombie Vampire, easily accessible by the level 8 bodies that Horus monsters provide. Get your gamble on, and mill mill mill your way to Masters 1 with Horus Tearlaments!

Tearlaments' gameplan is to mill as much as possible to trigger graveyard effects. Like every Tearlaments strategy, this deck aims to mill as much as possible and gain beneficial effects from those mills. The reliance on mills makes this strategy unpredictable and luck dependant, meaning that there are hardly any straightforward combos.

There are no straightforward "combos" for Tearlaments due to the random nature of the deck. Combos are hand/mill dependent - leaving the rest of the game up to the duelists individual skill, decision making and mental fortitude (that's the Tearlaments is considered as a difficult to pilot deck). Tearlaments are also infamous for requiring a great deal of skill, since the pilot has to be aware of the various interactions they have in the GY and the amount of cards left in their main deck.

GLHF Duelists!
